679/City-of-Brea-CAFR|title=City of Brea CAFR|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404074424/https://www.ci.brea.ca.us/DocumentCenter/View/679/City-of-Brea-CAFR|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of employees\n|-\n| 1\n|[[Bank of America]]\n|3,000\n|-\n| 2\n|[[Mercury Insurance Group]]\n|1,440\n|-\n| 3\n|[[Albertsons]]\n|1,321\n|-\n| 4\n|[[Beckman Coulter]]\n|906\n|-\n| 5\n|[[Brea Olinda Unified School District]]\n|713\n|-\n| 6\n|Kirkhill - TA Company\n|638\n|-\n| 7\n|[[Nationwide Mutual Insurance Company]]\n|460\n|-\n| 8\n|Bristol Industries\n|435\n|-\n| 9\n|Zodiac Inflight Innovations\n|390\n|-\n| 10\n|Peterson Brothers Construction\n|375\n|-\n|}\n\n==Education==\nThe city is served by the [[Brea Olinda Unified School District]] which operates six elementary schools, one junior high school ([[Brea Junior High School]]), one high school ([[Brea Olinda High School]]) and one continuation high school. A small portion of Brea is also directed to [[Sonora High School]] in [[La Habra, California|La Habra]] in the [[Fullerton Joint Union High School District]]. That small portion is also directed to the [[La Habra City School District]]. In addition, students can also take an assessment to place in nearby [[Troy High School (California)|Troy High School]] in [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], also part of the Fullerton High School District.\n\nThere are many private schools in Brea, the Brea Head Start (Pre) Brea Olinda Friends School (Pre-6), Brea Congregational Pre-School, Brea Foursquare Church (Pre-5), Brea United Methodist Pre-School (\"BUMPS\"), Carbon Canyon Christian School (K-12), Christ Lutheran School (Pre-8), St. Angela Merici Parish School (TK-8), and Montessori of Brea (K-6). Brea is also home to the Southern California College of Business and Law and the Southern California extension of [[Golden Gate Baptist Theological Seminary]].\n\n==School awards==\n[[File:Brea-edwards cinema night.jpg|thumb|right|Edwards Cinemas movie theater in Brea downtown.]]\nLocal schools have won several awards.  Brea Olinda High School and Olinda Elementary School have been named [[Blue Ribbon School]]s.  Additionally, Arovista Elementary, Country Hills Elementary, Fanning Elementary, Mariposa Elementary, Olinda Elementary, Brea Junior High and Brea Olinda High schools have been named [[California Distinguished School]]s.  Laurel Elementary received a Title I Academic Achievement Award.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Cody Fajardo]], Quarterback for the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]]\n* [[Stephanie J. Block]], Broadway actress/singer\n* [[James Cameron]], film director/producer/screenwriter\n* [[JoAnn Dean Killingsworth]], actress & dancer, first person to play [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]] at [[Disneyland]]<ref name=latimes>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Chawkins |title=JoAnn Dean Killingsworth dies at 91; Disneyland's first Snow White |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-joann-killingsworth-20150624-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 25, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Travis Denker]], Major League baseball player  ([[San Francisco Giants]])\n* [[Tommy Gallarda]], Pro Football player ([[Atlanta Falcons]])\n* [[James Hetfield]], musician ([[Metallica]])\n* [[Walter Johnson]], Major League baseball pitcher for the [[History of the Washington Senators (1901\u201360)#Team history|Washington Senators]]\n* [[Randy Jones (baseball)|Randy Jones]], Major League baseball player ([[San Diego Padres]])\n* [[Joe Maddon]], Major League baseball manager ([[Chicago Cubs]])\n* [[Alli Mauzey]], Broadway actress/singer\n* [[Evan Moore]], Pro Football player ([[Green Bay Packers]])\n* [[Jeanette Pohlen]], Women's National Basketball Association player ([[Indiana Fever]])\n* [[Cruz Reynoso]], jurist\n* [[Caroline Zhang]], figure skater\n* [[Nikki Ziering]], model and actress\n* [[Norma Zimmer]], singer\n\n==Sister cities==\n{{See also|List of sister cities in the United States}}\n\nBrea, California is [[twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Lagos de Moreno]], Mexico, since October 1969<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.brea.ca.us/index.aspx?NID=921 |title=Lagos de Moreno, Mexico |publisher=City of Brea |accessdate=May 10, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510165404/http://www.ci.brea.ca.us/index.aspx?NID=921 |archivedate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Hann\u014d, Saitama|Hanno]], Japan since January 5, 1981<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.brea.ca.us/index.aspx?NID=922 |title=Hanno, Japan |publisher=City of Brea |accessdate=May 10, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510170958/http://www.ci.brea.ca.us/index.aspx?NID=922 |archivedate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[Anseong]], South Korea<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.brea.ca.us/index.aspx?NID=923 |title=Anseong, Republic of Korea |publisher=City of Brea |accessdate=May 10, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510171239/http://www.ci.brea.ca.us/index.aspx?NID=923 |archivedate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Purl |last=Hardy |authorlink= |year= |title=History of Brea, California: From Early Oil Field Days to 1950 |edition= |publisher= |location= |id= |pages=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.breachamber.com/brea/history.asp |title=History of Brea |publisher=Brea Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=October 27, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061022210154/http://www.breachamber.com/brea/history.asp |archivedate=October 22, 2006 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.myoc.com/community/brea/history/ |title=My Orange County: Brea History |accessdate=2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050207121626/http://www.myoc.com/community/brea/history/ |archivedate=February 7, 2005}}\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Greater Los Angeles}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.breadowntown.com/|title=Brea Downtown|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2019|website=|accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cityofbrea.net/336/Police-Services|title=Brea Police Department|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.ci.brea.ca.us/291/Fire|title=Brea Fire Department|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2019|website=|accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.bousd.us/|title=Brea Olinda Unified School District|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2019|website=|accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.breasoccer.org/ |title=Brea Soccer Association |accessdate=June 25, 2007}}\n*[http://www.breagallery.com/203/Brea-Gallery City Of Brea Art Gallery]\n\n{{Brea, California}}\n{{Cities of Orange County, California}}\n{{Greater Los Angeles Area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Brea, California| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Incorporated cities and towns in California]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "ArchonBoi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brea,_California"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Kennedy Smith", "text_new": "{{Other people|Alexander Smith}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder |\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name= Alexander Kennedy Smith\n| honorific-suffix=\n| image=\n| caption=\n| nationality=[[Scotland|Scottish]] and [[Australia]]n\n|citizenship=[[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]]\n| order=31st [[Mayor of Melbourne]]\n| term_start=1875\n| term_end=1876\n| deputy          =\n| predecessor=[[James Gatehouse (politician)|James Gatehouse]]\n| successor= [[James Paterson (mayor)|James Paterson]]\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1824|7|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place=[[Cauldmill]], [[Roxburghshire]], Scotland\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1881|1|16|1824|7|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place=[[Melbourne]], Australia\n| spouse=\n| party=\n}}\n'''Alexander Kennedy Smith'''  (7 July 1824 \u2013 16 January 1881) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]]/[[Australian]] [[engineer]] and former [[Mayor of Melbourne]].\n\n==Early life==\nSmith was born in [[Cauldmill]] near [[Hawick]], [[Roxburghshire]], Scotland.  He was involved in the development of many of [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]]'s gas and water works during the 1850s and 1860s.\n\nSmith was sent{{Clarify|date=October 2009}} from Scotland to [[Melbourne]] in 1854 to manage and build the Melbourne Gas and Coke Co. works. Once that project was complete, Smith remained in Victoria and set up his own practice. He built gas works at [[Ballarat, Victoria|Ballarat]], [[Castlemaine, Victoria|Castlemaine]] and [[Bendigo, Victoria|Bendigo]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], as well as one at [[Newcastle, New South Wales]]. Smith also drew up plans and specifications for many other works in Australia and overseas. He was a consulting and [[locomotive]] engineer for the [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]], and worked as an engineer on the South Yarra Waterworks.\n\nSmith was also a member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from 1877 to 1881, member for the La Trobe Ward in the [[Melbourne City Council]] for fifteen years, and [[List of Mayors and Lord Mayors of Melbourne|Mayor of Melbourne]] from 1875 to 1876.\n\nSmith died of heart disease at his home in [[Studley Park]], Victoria, Australia.\n\n==Career highlights==\n*1846\u20131854 Engineer with the [[Great Western Railway|Great Western Railway Company]].\n*1853 \u2013 c.1857 Seconded to build and manage the Melbourne Gas and Coke Co. works \u2013 a five-year contract\n*1854 Arrived in Australia (Melbourne)\n*c.1857 \u2013  Civil and Consulting Engineer private practice established in [[Carlton, Victoria]]\n*1860 \u2013 ? Major in the Victorian Volunteer Artillery Regiment\n*1875\u20131876 Mayor of the City of Melbourne\n*1877\u20131881 Member for [[Electoral district of East Melbourne|East Melbourne]] in the Legislative Assembly\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.asap.unimelb.edu.au/bsparcs/biogs/P000152b.htm Bio at Melbourne University Bright Sparcs]\n*Jill Eastwood, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060159b.htm 'Smith, Alexander Kennedy (1824\u20131881)'], [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Vol.6, [[Melbourne University Press|MUP]], 1976, p.&nbsp;139\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Alexander Kennedy}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:Australian engineers]]\n[[Category:Scottish civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Mayors and Lord Mayors of Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Victoria (Australia) state politicians]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-engineer-stub}}\n{{Australia-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Alexander Smith}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder |\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name= Alexander Kennedy Smith\n| honorific-suffix=\n| image=\n| caption=\n| nationality=[[Scotland|Scottish]] and [[Australia]]n\n|citizenship=[[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]]\n| order=31st [[Mayor of Melbourne]]\n| term_start=1875\n| term_end=1876\n| deputy          =\n| predecessor=[[James Gatehouse (politician)|James Gatehouse]]\n| successor= [[James Paterson (mayor)|James Paterson]]\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1824|7|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place=[[Cauldmill]], [[Roxburghshire]], Scotland\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1881|1|16|1824|7|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place=[[Melbourne]], Australia\n| spouse=\n| party=\n}}\n'''Alexander Kennedy Smith'''  (7 July 1824 \u2013 16 January 1881) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]]/[[Australian]] [[engineer]] and former [[Mayor of Melbourne]].\n\n==Early life==\nSmith was born in [[Cauldmill]] near [[Hawick]], [[Roxburghshire]], Scotland.  He was involved in the development of many of [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]]'s gas and water works during the 1850s and 1860s.\n\nSmith was sent{{Clarify|date=October 2009}} from Scotland to [[Melbourne]] in 1854 to manage and build the Melbourne Gas and Coke Co. works. Once that project was complete, Smith remained in Victoria and set up his own practice. He built gas works at [[Ballarat, Victoria|Ballarat]], [[Castlemaine, Victoria|Castlemaine]] and [[Bendigo, Victoria|Bendigo]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], as well as one at [[Newcastle, New South Wales]]. Smith also drew up plans and specifications for many other works in Australia and overseas. He was a consulting and [[locomotive]] engineer for the [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]], and worked as an engineer on the South Yarra Waterworks.\n\nSmith was also a member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from 1877 to 1881, member for the La Trobe Ward in the [[Melbourne City Council]] for fifteen years, and [[List of Mayors and Lord Mayors of Melbourne|Mayor of Melbourne]] from 1875 to 1876.\n\nSmith died of heart disease at his home in [[Studley Park]], Victoria, Australia.\n\n==Career highlights==\n*1846\u20131854 Engineer with the [[Great Western Railway|Great Western Railway Company]].\n*1853 - c.1857 Seconded to build and manage the Melbourne Gas and Coke Co. works - a five-year contract\n*1854 Arrived in Australia (Melbourne)\n*c.1857 -  Civil and Consulting Engineer private practice established in [[Carlton, Victoria]]\n*1860 - ? Major in the Victorian Volunteer Artillery Regiment\n*1875\u20131876 Mayor of the City of Melbourne\n*1877\u20131881 Member for [[Electoral district of East Melbourne|East Melbourne]] in the Legislative Assembly\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.asap.unimelb.edu.au/bsparcs/biogs/P000152b.htm Bio at Melbourne University Bright Sparcs]\n*Jill Eastwood, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060159b.htm 'Smith, Alexander Kennedy (1824\u20131881)'], [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Vol.6, [[Melbourne University Press|MUP]], 1976, p.&nbsp;139\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Alexander Kennedy}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:Australian engineers]]\n[[Category:Scottish civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Mayors and Lord Mayors of Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Victoria (Australia) state politicians]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-engineer-stub}}\n{{Australia-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Kennedy_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Atlanta annexations and wards", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\nFrom its incorporation in 1847, the municipal boundaries [[Atlanta, Georgia]] were extended repeatedly from a small area around its railroad station to today's city covering {{Convert|131.7|mi2|km2}}.\n\nPrior to 1954, Atlanta was divided into political divisions called wards. The number of wards were increased as the city grew.\n\n==List of annexations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Sortable list of acres annexed per year\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Area annexed\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Areas annexed\n|-\n| [[#1952|1952]] || {{convert|51922|acre}} || [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], Adams Park, [[Neighborhoods of Atlanta#Southwestern Atlanta|Southwest Atlanta]], [[Lakewood Heights (Atlanta)|Lakewood]]\n|-\n| [[#1910|1910]] || {{convert|5606|acre}} || [[Ansley Park]],  [[Sherwood Forest (Atlanta)|Sherwood Forest]], north [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]],  [[Hemphill Avenue]], east [[Bankhead (Atlanta)|Bankhead]],<br>north [[English Avenue]], [[Washington Park (Atlanta)|Washington Park]], [[Mozley Park]], Ashview Heights, west [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]], [[Westview (Atlanta)|Westview]]\n|-\n| [[#1953|1953]] || {{convert|4769|acre}} || [[Ben Hill (Atlanta)|Ben Hill]], [[Greenbriar (Atlanta)|Greenbriar]], et al.\n|-\n| [[#1909|1909]] || {{convert|2612|acre}} ||[[Copenhill]], part of [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]], [[Edgewood (Atlanta)|Edgewood]], [[Reynoldstown]], [[East Atlanta]]\n|-\n| [[#1922|1922]] || {{convert|2481|acre}} || [[Kirkwood (Atlanta)|Kirkwood]], parts of [[Virginia-Highland]] and [[Morningside/Lenox Park|Morningside]], [[Ormewood Park]] \n|-\n| [[#1866|1866]] || {{convert|2476|acre}} ||expand city limits to a one-and-a-half mile radius\n|-\n| 1958 || {{convert|1832|acre}} || Areas west of Niskey Lake Road in Southwest Atlanta<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=48 |title=Atlanta Annexation database, case no. ANX-1958-001 |access-date=2013-01-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226063803/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=48 |archive-date=2013-12-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| 1967 || {{convert|1765|acre}} ||\n|-\n| [[#1889|1889]] || {{convert|1547|acre}} ||expand city limits to one and three-quarter mile radius\n|-\n| [[#1928|1928]] || {{convert|1429|acre}} || [[East Lake (Atlanta)|East Lake]], [[Chosewood Park]]\n|-\n| 1925 || {{convert|1164|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1950 || {{convert|905|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1904 || {{convert|822|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2006 || {{convert|766|acre}} || [[Midwest Cascade]], Horseshoe Community\n|-\n| 2018 || {{convert|744|acre}} || [[Emory University]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta]] (Egleston)\n|-\n| [[#1894|1894]] || {{convert|665|acre}} || [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]]\n|-\n| 1923 || {{convert|411|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1926 || {{convert|408|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1945 || {{convert|355|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1863 || {{convert|286|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1968 || {{convert|270|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2007 || {{convert|266|acre}} ||\n[[Decatur, Georgia|Decatur]]\n|-\n| 2015 || {{convert|200|acre}} ||\nOlmestead at East Lake\n|-\n| 1913 || {{convert|197|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1957 || {{convert|161|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1963 || {{convert|158|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1940 || {{convert|150|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1895 || {{convert|143|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2016 || {{convert|129.14|acre}} ||Northwest Cascade\n|-\n| 1960 || {{convert|110|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1932 || {{convert|110|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2013 || {{convert|108.43|acre}} ||Cascade Road Landfill\n|-\n| 1916 || {{convert|103|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1969 || {{convert|75|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1915 || {{convert|75|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1854 || {{convert|69|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1976 || {{convert|68|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1973 || {{convert|49|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2003 || {{convert|47|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1962 || {{convert|40|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2008 || {{convert|39|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1970 || {{convert|33|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1930 || {{convert|31|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1949 || {{convert|30|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2009 || {{convert|24|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1934 || {{convert|24|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1979 || {{convert|21|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1954 || {{convert|17|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1978 || {{convert|17|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2016 || {{convert|16|acre}} || University Drive and Spring Valley Lane\n|-\n| 1943 || {{convert|13|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1914 || {{convert|9|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1965 || {{convert|2|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2005 || {{convert|1|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2010 || {{convert|0.14|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2018 || {{convert|744|acre|ha}}<ref name=NiesseEmoryannexed>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/city-atlanta-expansion-emory-and-cdc-approved/kMYzghHbvzD6THTyWpN1zH/|title=City of Atlanta's expansion to Emory and CDC approved|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=December 5, 2017|quote=The city\u2019s 744-acre addition covers [...] Children\u2019s Healthcare of Atlanta.}}</ref> || [[Centers for Disease Control]], [[Emory University]], [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta - Egleston Hospital]]\n|}\n\n==Annexations by year==\n\n===1847===\nCity is incorporated \u2014 city limits are a {{convert|1|mi|adj=on}} radius from the zero mile marker of the [[Western & Atlantic Railroad]]. City covers {{convert|3.14|mi2|abbr=on}}, {{convert|2010.6|acre}}.\n\n===1854===\n[[Image:Atlanta-ward-1854.png|thumb|200px|right|Layout of Atlanta's five wards (1854\u20131871)]]\nThe 1848 charter only specified election of six citywide councilmembers, but on January 9, 1854, an ordinance was adopted that divided the town into five wards and two councilmen from each ward would be elected to coincide with the completion of the first [[City Halls of Atlanta|official city hall]].\nThe next election with the new rules on January 15, 1855, decided those first Ward bosses who would serve with the short-term mayor, [[Allison Nelson]].\nThe boundaries were as follows:\n{{anchor|first_ward}}\n*'''First''' (yellow): all land west of the W&A Railroad and Whitehall Street. This diverse ward had concentrations of industry and working-class people (such as railroad men) in the northern and western parts but the eastern section was home to some of Atlanta's wealthiest citizens, such as [[Richard Peters (Atlanta)|Richard Peters]].\n{{anchor|second_ward}}\n*'''Second''' (red): land south of Georgia RR between Whitehall and McDonough. This wealthy section included the bulk of the town's wholesalers, warehouses, grocers and hotels. The residential areas included people like Dr. [[Joseph Thompson (doctor)|Joseph Thompson]].\n{{anchor|third_ward}}\n*'''Third''' (green): land south of Georgia RR and east of McDonough. This ward included the new city hall, a number of mills along the railroad and the east many large estates including that of [[Lemuel P. Grant]].\n{{anchor|fourth_ward}}\n*'''Fourth''' (blue): north of Georgia RR and east of Ivy. This ward had two of the roughest sections of town; the red-light district along Decatur Street (including [[Murrell's Row]]) and [[Slabtown, Atlanta, Georgia|Slabtown]] but the northern part was home to mostly small farms.\n{{anchor|fifth_ward}}\n*'''Fifth''' (violet): west of Ivy and north of W&A Railroad. This ward contained the large homes along [[Peachtree Street]] and the southern part, [[Fairlie-Poplar]] was also largely residential with warehousing along the western part.\n\n===1866===\nOn March 12, city limits expand to a one-and-a-half mile radius from [[Atlanta Union Station (1853)|Union Depot]].<ref name=gis>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/doc_archive/raw/d004000/p004333.pdf City of Atlanta GIS, Map of Annexations]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/tdgh-mar/mar12.htm \"March 12\", ''This Day in Georgia History'', Digital Library of Georgia]</ref>\n\n===1871===\n[[Image:Atlanta-wards-1871.png|thumb|200px|left|Layout of Atlanta's seven wards (1871\u20131874)]]\n\nDuring a huge boom of post-war building, two new wards were added from parts of the First, Fourth and Fifth to reflect the changing look of the city. \n*[[Sixth Ward (Atlanta)|Sixth Ward]] (aqua): established October 1871 as the half of the First Ward north of Hunter St (MLK). This division left the wealthy in the First ward and gave the working-class people to the north two councilmen of their own.\n*[[Seventh Ward (Atlanta)|Seventh Ward]] (grey): established December 2, 1871 of parts of the Fourth and Fifth. Specifically from the \"junction of Houston and Pryor streets, thence through lot nineteen, between blocks three, one and two, five and six, to the city limits; thence northerly along the city limits to Peachtree Street; thence south along Peachtree Street and Pryor Street to the beginning.\" And the Fourth was extended \"from Ivy Street west to Pryor, and from Houston Street south to the railroad, and that Pryor Street shall be the line between the fourth and fifth wards, and Pryor and Peachtree streets between the fifth and seventh wards.\" This gave the red-light district to the Fourth and created a new Ward of mostly farmers and to the west, fine residences along Ivy and the east side of Peachtree.\n\n===1874===\n[[Image:Atlanta-wards-1874.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Layout of Atlanta's five wards (1874 to 1883)]]\nA new city charter was approved by [[James Milton Smith|Governor Smith]] on February 28, 1874, which reduced the number of wards back to five and created a bi-cameral council of two councilmen from each ward and a second body of three at-large aldermen was established.\nEach year one of the aldermen would be up for election and during his last year in office would serve as president of the other body.\nThey acted separately on finances but together for all other business.\n\nThe new ward layout was as follows:\n*[[First Ward (Atlanta)|First Ward]] (yellow) was bounded by [[Western & Atlantic Railroad]], Foundry St, south around the city limits to modern [[Peachtree Street]]\n*[[Second Ward (Atlanta)|Second Ward]] (red) was bounded by the [[Georgia Railroad]], Whitehall south to city limits then north-east to McDonough (Capital Ave) and up to the railroad\n*[[Third Ward (Atlanta)|Third Ward]] (green) was bounded by Butler (Jesse Hill Dr) and McDonough Streets south to the city limits north-east to Georgia RR, then west to Butler\n*[[Fourth Ward (Atlanta)|Fourth Ward]] (blue) from Pryor and tracks east on Georgia RR to city limits then north west to West Peachtree and south to origin.\n*[[Fifth Ward (Atlanta)|Fifth Ward]] (purple) from Pryor and tracks north-east to Peachtree, then West Peachtree to city limits, south-west to Foundry and W&A RR and east to origin\n\n===1883===\n[[Image:Atlanta-wards-1883.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Layout of Atlanta's six wards (1883 to 1894)]]\n\nOn November 5, 1883 a [[Sixth Ward (Atlanta)|Sixth Ward]] (beige) was carved out of the Fourth and Fifth Wards.\nIts boundaries started at Butler and the [[Georgia Railroad|GRR]] (today's Grady Hospital) north to [[North Avenue (Atlanta)|North Ave]] at Myrtle St, then up Myrtle to the city limit at 3rd St.\nFollow the arc of the city limit to Williams, south to Cain (International) then James (Church) to Forsyth south to the tracks then east on the tracks to origin.\nThis separated the wealthy Peachtree corridor from the other parts of north Atlanta. (Garrett Vol II, p.&nbsp;53\u201354)\n\n===1889===\nExpansion of city limits to one and three-quarters radius from [[Atlanta Union Station (1871)|union depot]].<ref name=gis/>\n\n===1894===\nWhen [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]] was annexed into the city in 1894, it became a new [[Seventh Ward (Atlanta)|Seventh Ward]].\n\n===1904===\n{{convert|822|acre|ha}} annexed - the southern part of what is now Midtown was already within the 1889 limits, but in 1904 the city annexes most of the rest of what is now Midtown: this is an area bounded by the 1889 circular city limits on the south, and West Peachtree St. on the west, stretching north up to but not including Ansley Park (roughly 6th to 16th Streets), Piedmont Park, the remainder of Historic Midtown east to what is now the [[BeltLine]]. this includes a strip of what is now the [[Old Fourth Ward]] between the 1889 limits and the BeltLine.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=126 City of Atlanta annexation database, Case ANX-1904-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1905===\nFurther expansion of the city limits was part of a long effort.\n\nIn October 1897 [[Frank P. Rice]] drove a failed proposal to annex [[Pittsburgh (Atlanta)|Pittsburgh]], [[Reynoldstown]], [[Bellwood (Atlanta)|Bellwood]], and what was then called \"north Atlanta\".<ref>[\"Suburbs will not be annexed now: The Rice measure tabled by Council yesterday afternoon\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', October 27, 1897]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/atlantayesterday00horn/atlantayesterday00horn_djvu.txt John R. Hornady, \"Atlanta yesterday, today and tomorrow\", 1922]</ref>\n\n\"North Atlanta\" was defined at the time roughly as today's [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]], [[Georgia Tech]], and [[English Avenue]]:<ref>[\"Outside Folks Hot After Rice\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', October 24, 1897]</ref>\n* today's Midtown between Myrtle St. in the [[Midtown Historic District (Atlanta, Georgia)|Midtown Historic District]] and Cherry St., now inside the Georgia Tech campus, as far north as 14th St (then called Wilson Ave.)\n* most of what is now the Georgia Tech campus, south of what was then 5th Street\n* the area west of Georgia Tech, south of Jefferson St., as far west as Ashby St. (now Lowery Blvd.), including today's English Avenue neighborhood\n\nIn 1902 a special committee made a new proposal to annex those areas as well as \"Bonnie Brae\", [[Copenhill]], and the \"St. Charles Avenue\" area (in today's [[Virginia Highland]]). By then, \"north Atlanta\" was being referred to as \"Peachtree\".<ref>[\"New Limits Outlined for Greater Atlanta\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', Apr. 30, 1902]</ref>\n\nIn 1905, the [[Eighth Ward (Atlanta)|Eighth Ward]] was added. An act of the [[Georgia General Assembly]] was enacted on August 3, 1904 which designated the area from then current city limits (at 6th St and West Peachtree), north to 15th St, then east to Piedmont Ave, then northeast to [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]] (basically follow Piedmont to the [[Ansley Park]] area), then southwardly along the railway the limits. The act also took part of the Sixth Ward north of North Ave. into the new Eighth Ward.\n\n===1909===\nOn January 1, 1909, a Ninth Ward was formed out of just annexed [[Copenhill]], part of [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]], [[Edgewood (Atlanta)|Edgewood]], [[Reynoldstown]] and [[East Atlanta]]. Edgewood alone had had its own city government before the annexation.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7qpif6-Z5o4C&pg=PA539 ''Atlanta and Environs: A Chronicle of Its People and Events, 1880s-1930s'', Franklin M. Garrett, p.539]</ref>\n\n===1910===\n\n====Annexations====\nAnnexation of {{convert|3510|acre|ha sqmi|2|lk=on}} to the north and west:<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=118 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1910-004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210173311/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=118 |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref><ref name=annexationmap>[http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/MapsTest/id/155/rec/126 Annexation Map of Atlanta, City of Atlanta, revised 1981] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814210044/http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/MapsTest/id/155/rec/126 |date=2013-08-14 }}</ref>\n*[[Ansley Park]] and most of [[Sherwood Forest (Atlanta)|Sherwood Forest]]\n*[[Peachtree Street]] from 15h street north to Palisades Road in southern [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]]\n*the area that is now the [[Georgia Tech]] campus that was not already part of the city, including the [[Hemphill Avenue]] neighborhood\n*[[Bankhead (Atlanta)|Bankhead]] east of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] line\n*Remainder of [[English Avenue]] (northern part) that was not already part of the city\n*[[Washington Park (Atlanta)|Washington Park]]\n*What is now [[Mozley Park]], then called Battle Hill\n*Ashview Heights\n*remainder of today's [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]] (western part) that was not already part of the city\n*most of [[Westview (Atlanta)|Westview]]\n\nAnnexation of {{convert|2011|acre|ha sqmi|2|lk=on}} including the town of [[Oakland City (Atlanta)|Oakland City]] and from the previous city limits south to the [[BeltLine]]: [[Adair Park]], most of [[Pittsburgh (Atlanta)|Pittsburgh]], southern [[Summerhill (Atlanta)|Summerhill]], southern/eastern edges of [[Grant Park (Atlanta)|Grant Park]] neighborhood.<ref name=annexationmap/><ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=119 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1910-003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210172412/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=119 |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n\nAnnexation of the blocks surrounding Brown Park (now Brownwood Park) in [[East Atlanta]] - Moreland east to Stokesland and Glenwood south to the current city limits.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=120 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1910-002]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====New Tenth Ward====\nA new Tenth Ward was created. The eastern boundary was McDaniel Street. The southwestern boundary was Whitehall Street to the Central of Georgia Railroad, and from there along the railroad to a point just south of the BeltLine. From there, the boundary ran due west to a prolongation of Holderness Street south of the BeltLine, and from there southwest to the junction of Campbellton and Utoy roads. Then due east along the north boundary of Fort McPherson to the Central of Georgia Railroad. Then south along that railway line to a point between Osborne and Astor avenues, then east to Sylvan Road, then north to the BeltLine, then east to McDaniel Street.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ByTgAtilbi4C&pg=PA558 ''Atlanta and Environs: A Chronicle of Its People and Events, 1880s-1930s'', Franklin M. Garrett p.558]</ref>\n\nThis included:\n*New territory from the annexations including Oakland City\n*Territory from the Second Ward west of McDaniel Street\n*Territory from the Seventh Ward east of the Central of Georgia Railroad\n\n===1919===\nEleventh Ward created from part of the Ninth Ward (area south of the [[Georgia Railroad and Banking Company|Georgia railroad line]]) and from part of the Third Ward. The new ward corresponds to East Atlanta, Ormewood Park, and other adjacent areas.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Fxg4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA834 ''Acts passed by the General Assembly of Georgia, 1919'', p.834]</ref>\n\n===1922===\n*[[Kirkwood (Atlanta)|Kirkwood]]<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=107 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-006]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> annexed ({{convert|975|acre|ha sqmi|1}})\n*North part of [[Virginia-Highland]] and south part of [[Morningside/Lenox Park]] annexed ({{convert|858|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=110 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-003]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=111 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-002]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*[[Ormewood Park]] annexed ({{convert|482|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=112 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1923===\nIn June 1923 there was a failed movement to annex [[College Park, Georgia|College Park]], [[East Point, Georgia|East Point]], and [[Hapeville, Georgia|Hapeville]].<ref>[http://www.fold3.com/image/#25|102033847 \"Steps are taken for annexation of three suburbs\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', June 30, 1923, p.1]</ref>\n\n===1928===\n*[[East Lake (Atlanta)|East Lake]] annexed ({{convert|717|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=84 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1928-004]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> as the 12th ward. \n*[[Chosewood Park]] annexed. ({{convert|626|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=87 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1928-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1929===\nA Thirteenth Ward was created as the section of the Ninth Ward north of St. Charles and east of the [[Belt Line (Atlanta)|Belt Line]] to the west side of Briarcliff and north the corporate limits. (most of today's [[Virginia-Highland]])\n\n===1937===\nOn March 14, 1935, the legislature reduced the number of wards from 13 to 6 and the thirty-nine member city council is cut to eighteen members effective January 1, 1937. The wards were combined as such:\n*First: old 2nd & 3rd (south from Central RR to Grant Park)\n*Second: old 11th & 12th (southeast: Ormewood, East Atlanta and East Lake)\n*Third: old 1st, 5th & 6th (northwest from Central RR around to three blocks east of Peachtree)\n*Fourth: old 7th & 10th (from West End to Oakland City)\n*Fifth: old 4th & 8th (from Georgia RR up to Piedmont Park and Ansley west of the [[Belt Line (Atlanta)|Belt Line]])\n*Sixth: old 9th & 13th (everything east of the Belt Line and north of Georgia RR: Inman Park, Druid Hills, etc.)<ref>Garrett, Vol. II, p.927</ref>\n\n===1952===\n[[File:Atlanta annexation 1952.jpg|thumb|300px|1952 annexation]]\nIn 1951, after a failed 1947 referendum and two other failed attempts, the state legislature passed a \"Plan of Improvement\" by which on Jan. 1, 1952, the city annexed {{convert|51470|acre|ha sqmi|1|lk=on}} in  [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], Adams Park, [[Neighborhoods of Atlanta#Southwestern Atlanta|Southwest Atlanta]] & [[Lakewood Heights (Atlanta)|Lakewood]].<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=66 City of Atlanta Annexation database, Case ANX-1952-005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210173458/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=66 |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref> This was by far the largest expansion in Atlanta's history, tripling the size of the city to {{convert|118|mi2|km2}} and adding 100,000 residents. This helped spread the burden of providing public services by adding to the base a large group of mostly more affluent residents. The annexation was viewed as a triumph of [[William Hartsfield|Mayor Hartsfield]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_WuW4GAUg9EC&lpg=PA71&dq=buckhead%20annexed%20square%20miles&pg=PA86 | title=William Berry Hartsfield: Mayor of Atlanta| isbn=9780820335445| last1=Martin| first1=Harold H.| date=May 2010}}</ref>\n\nAtlanta would in the 1970s again try, but without success, to repeat the process by state legislation to annex what is now [[Sandy Springs, Georgia|Sandy Springs]] to Atlanta.<ref>[http://www.sandysprings.com/history.aspx ''City of Sandy Springs'', \"History\"]</ref>\n\n===1953===\nAnnexation of [[Ben Hill (Atlanta)|Ben Hill]], [[Greenbriar (Atlanta)|Greenbriar]] and other adjacent areas in far southwestern Atlanta.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=59 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1953-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1954===\nThe ward system is ended. No longer a bicameral body, only a board of six aldermen with a Vice-Mayor serving as president of the board. All positions were elected citywide. (For post-ward setup, see [[Political structure of Atlanta]]).\n\n===Annexations since 1953===\nSince 1953, multiple small annexations (and deannexations) to the City of Atlanta have occurred, in two periods from 1954-1979 and 2003-2010. No annexations took place from 1979 to 2003.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?page=1, 2, 3, 4, 5 City of Atlanta GIS Annexations database]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMultiple small areas adjacent to southwestern Atlanta were annexed including [[Midwest Cascade]], Cascade Glen, and the Horseshoe Community.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?page=2 |title=City of Atlanta GIS Annexations database |access-date=2011-11-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425231716/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?page=2 |archive-date=2012-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Sandtown, Georgia|Sandtown]]'s 2007 petition for annexation was put on hold.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=2 Atlanta annexations database, case ANX-2006-006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413155440/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=2 |date=April 13, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThese annexations added a few thousand residents, and approximately three square miles, including areas mostly in the southwest of the city, but also small parcels in the east and north of the city.\n\n====Emory University and Centers for Disease Control annexation====\nIn December 2017, the Atlanta City Council approved an annexation request by [[Emory University]], the [[Centers for Disease Control]], [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta - Egleston Hospital]], and other contiguous property owners in the [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]] neighborhood of [[Dekalb County, Georgia|Dekalb County]]. The annexation was effective January 1, 2018.<ref name=NiesseEmoryannexed/> In June 2017 the university leadership formally petitioned the City of Atlanta to annex it.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stafford, Leon|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/emory-university-formally-files-petition-become-part-atlanta/KkN3nSaOPuSOKPGICIxnwJ/|title=Emory University formally files petition to become part of Atlanta|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-06-27|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> To comply with the requirement that an annexed area be adjacent to the existing city limits, the university purchased a residence partially within the then-city limits.<ref>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/path-for-emory-university-join-atlanta-runs-through-backyard/7JRjnX8DZC9KbdXdwjzkXJ/|title=Path for Emory University to join Atlanta runs through a backyard|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-03-03|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> The city government also entered into a settlement with the [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]] government to settle a dispute, paving the way for the annexation.<ref>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|author2=Leon Stafford|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/deal-between-atlanta-and-dekalb-clears-way-for-city-expansion-emory/OVby4dKuzmPSh8W4yQlcyO/|title=Deal between Atlanta and DeKalb clears way for city\u2019s expansion to Emory|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-09-26|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nDue to the taxable revenue involved, there was a dispute over whether the area would remain in the [[DeKalb County School District]] or transition to [[Atlanta Public Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/emory-annexation-won-finished-time-for-atlanta-elections/5XmFt1qUhAAH4gAn8yF5QM/|title=9 students and $2.3M stand in the way of Emory\u2019s annexation to Atlanta|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-10-16|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> In 2016 Emory University made a statement that \"Annexation of Emory into the City of Atlanta will not change school districts, since neighboring communities like [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]] will still be self-determining regarding annexation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.emory.edu/stories/2016/08/upress_atlanta_annexation_statement/index.html|title=\nEmory University statement on possible annexation|publisher=[[Emory University]]|date=2016-08-19|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> The annexed area ultimately went to APS,<ref name=NiesseEmoryannexed/> and as part of a 2019 settlement Emory would help establish school-based clinics for DeKalb schools.<ref>{{cite web|author=McCray, Vanessa|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/aps-dekalb-annexation-deal-could-pay-for-six-school-health-clinics/5mbGjr9WelTTKnoIUmArUJ/?fbclid=IwAR01FkInaRhB_qxC677slVPgDIMKYSoXUdFHbTW1PX8iaGJfwF-fX3gj3g4|title=APS, DeKalb annexation deal could pay for six school health clinics|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2019-12-10|accessdate=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | last=Garrett | first=Franklin Miller | authorlink=Franklin Garrett | year=1969 | title=Atlanta and Environs: A Chronicle of Its People and Events | publisher=University of Georgia Press | location=Georgia | isbn=0-8203-0263-5}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060319162755/http://apps.atlantaga.gov/citycoul/history.htm City Council history]\n*Stone, Clarence N., ''Regime Politics Governing Atlanta: 1946\u20131988'', 1989, University Press of Kansas\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130814210044/http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/MapsTest/id/155/rec/126 Detailed map of Atlanta annexations by City of Atlanta at Georgia State Library digital collections]\n**[https://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/digital/collection/atlmaps/id/155 Annexation Map of Atlanta from the 1980s]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Atlanta history}}\n\n[[Category:History of Atlanta|Ward System]]\n[[Category:Government of Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Geography of Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\nFrom its incorporation in 1847, the municipal boundaries [[Atlanta, Georgia]] were extended repeatedly from a small area around its railroad station to today's city covering {{Convert|131.7|mi2|km2}}.\n\nPrior to 1954, Atlanta was divided into political divisions called wards. The number of wards were increased as the city grew.\n\n==List of annexations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Sortable list of acres annexed per year\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Area annexed\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Areas annexed\n|-\n| [[#1952|1952]] || {{convert|51922|acre}} || [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], Adams Park, [[Neighborhoods of Atlanta#Southwestern Atlanta|Southwest Atlanta]], [[Lakewood Heights (Atlanta)|Lakewood]]\n|-\n| [[#1910|1910]] || {{convert|5606|acre}} || [[Ansley Park]],  [[Sherwood Forest (Atlanta)|Sherwood Forest]], north [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]],  [[Hemphill Avenue]], east [[Bankhead (Atlanta)|Bankhead]],<br>north [[English Avenue]], [[Washington Park (Atlanta)|Washington Park]], [[Mozley Park]], Ashview Heights, west [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]], [[Westview (Atlanta)|Westview]]\n|-\n| [[#1953|1953]] || {{convert|4769|acre}} || [[Ben Hill (Atlanta)|Ben Hill]], [[Greenbriar (Atlanta)|Greenbriar]], et al.\n|-\n| [[#1909|1909]] || {{convert|2612|acre}} ||[[Copenhill]], part of [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]], [[Edgewood (Atlanta)|Edgewood]], [[Reynoldstown]], [[East Atlanta]]\n|-\n| [[#1922|1922]] || {{convert|2481|acre}} || [[Kirkwood (Atlanta)|Kirkwood]], parts of [[Virginia-Highland]] and [[Morningside/Lenox Park|Morningside]], [[Ormewood Park]] \n|-\n| [[#1866|1866]] || {{convert|2476|acre}} ||expand city limits to a one-and-a-half mile radius\n|-\n| 1958 || {{convert|1832|acre}} || Areas west of Niskey Lake Road in Southwest Atlanta<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=48 |title=Atlanta Annexation database, case no. ANX-1958-001 |access-date=2013-01-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226063803/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=48 |archive-date=2013-12-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| 1967 || {{convert|1765|acre}} ||\n|-\n| [[#1889|1889]] || {{convert|1547|acre}} ||expand city limits to one and three-quarter mile radius\n|-\n| [[#1928|1928]] || {{convert|1429|acre}} || [[East Lake (Atlanta)|East Lake]], [[Chosewood Park]]\n|-\n| 1925 || {{convert|1164|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1950 || {{convert|905|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1904 || {{convert|822|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2006 || {{convert|766|acre}} || [[Midwest Cascade]], Horseshoe Community\n|-\n| 2018 || {{convert|744|acre}} || [[Emory University]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta]] (Egleston)\n|-\n| [[#1894|1894]] || {{convert|665|acre}} || [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]]\n|-\n| 1923 || {{convert|411|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1926 || {{convert|408|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1945 || {{convert|355|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1863 || {{convert|286|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1968 || {{convert|270|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2007 || {{convert|266|acre}} ||\n[[Decatur, Georgia|Decatur]]\n|-\n| 2015 || {{convert|200|acre}} ||\nOlmestead at East Lake\n|-\n| 1913 || {{convert|197|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1957 || {{convert|161|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1963 || {{convert|158|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1940 || {{convert|150|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1895 || {{convert|143|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2016 || {{convert|129.14|acre}} ||Northwest Cascade\n|-\n| 1960 || {{convert|110|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1932 || {{convert|110|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2013 || {{convert|108.43|acre}} ||Cascade Road Landfill\n|-\n| 1916 || {{convert|103|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1969 || {{convert|75|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1915 || {{convert|75|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1854 || {{convert|69|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1976 || {{convert|68|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1973 || {{convert|49|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2003 || {{convert|47|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1962 || {{convert|40|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2008 || {{convert|39|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1970 || {{convert|33|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1930 || {{convert|31|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1949 || {{convert|30|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2009 || {{convert|24|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1934 || {{convert|24|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1979 || {{convert|21|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1954 || {{convert|17|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1978 || {{convert|17|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2016 || {{convert|16|acre}} || University Drive and Spring Valley Lane\n|-\n| 1943 || {{convert|13|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1914 || {{convert|9|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 1965 || {{convert|2|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2005 || {{convert|1|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2010 || {{convert|0.14|acre}} ||\n|-\n| 2018 || {{convert|744|acre|ha}}<ref name=NiesseEmoryannexed>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/city-atlanta-expansion-emory-and-cdc-approved/kMYzghHbvzD6THTyWpN1zH/|title=City of Atlanta's expansion to Emory and CDC approved|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=December 5, 2017|quote=The city\u2019s 744-acre addition covers [...] Children\u2019s Healthcare of Atlanta.}}</ref> || [[Centers for Disease Control]], [[Emory University]], [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta - Egleston Hospital]]\n|}\n\n==Annexations by year==\n\n===1847===\nCity is incorporated \u2014 city limits are a {{convert|1|mi|adj=on}} radius from the zero mile marker of the [[Western & Atlantic Railroad]]. City covers {{convert|3.14|mi2|abbr=on}}, {{convert|2010.6|acre}}.\n\n===1854===\n[[Image:Atlanta-ward-1854.png|thumb|200px|right|Layout of Atlanta's five wards (1854\u20131871)]]\nThe 1848 charter only specified election of six citywide councilmembers, but on January 9, 1854, an ordinance was adopted that divided the town into five wards and two councilmen from each ward would be elected to coincide with the completion of the first [[City Halls of Atlanta|official city hall]].\nThe next election with the new rules on January 15, 1855, decided those first Ward bosses who would serve with the short-term mayor, [[Allison Nelson]].\nThe boundaries were as follows:\n{{anchor|first_ward}}\n*'''First''' (yellow): all land west of the W&A Railroad and Whitehall Street. This diverse ward had concentrations of industry and working-class people (such as railroad men) in the northern and western parts but the eastern section was home to some of Atlanta's wealthiest citizens, such as [[Richard Peters (Atlanta)|Richard Peters]].\n{{anchor|second_ward}}\n*'''Second''' (red): land south of Georgia RR between Whitehall and McDonough. This wealthy section included the bulk of the town's wholesalers, warehouses, grocers and hotels. The residential areas included people like Dr. [[Joseph Thompson (doctor)|Joseph Thompson]].\n{{anchor|third_ward}}\n*'''Third''' (green): land south of Georgia RR and east of McDonough. This ward included the new city hall, a number of mills along the railroad and the east many large estates including that of [[Lemuel P. Grant]].\n{{anchor|fourth_ward}}\n*'''Fourth''' (blue): north of Georgia RR and east of Ivy. This ward had two of the roughest sections of town; the red-light district along Decatur Street (including [[Murrell's Row]]) and [[Slabtown, Atlanta, Georgia|Slabtown]] but the northern part was home to mostly small farms.\n{{anchor|fifth_ward}}\n*'''Fifth''' (violet): west of Ivy and north of W&A Railroad. This ward contained the large homes along [[Peachtree Street]] and the southern part, [[Fairlie-Poplar]] was also largely residential with warehousing along the western part.\n\n===1866===\nOn March 12, city limits expand to a one-and-a-half mile radius from [[Atlanta Union Station (1853)|Union Depot]].<ref name=gis>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/doc_archive/raw/d004000/p004333.pdf City of Atlanta GIS, Map of Annexations]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/tdgh-mar/mar12.htm \"March 12\", ''This Day in Georgia History'', Digital Library of Georgia]</ref>\n\n===1871===\n[[Image:Atlanta-wards-1871.png|thumb|200px|left|Layout of Atlanta's seven wards (1871\u20131874)]]\n\nDuring a huge boom of post-war building, two new wards were added from parts of the First, Fourth and Fifth to reflect the changing look of the city. \n*[[Sixth Ward (Atlanta)|Sixth Ward]] (aqua): established October 1871 as the half of the First Ward north of Hunter St (MLK). This division left the wealthy in the First ward and gave the working-class people to the north two councilmen of their own.\n*[[Seventh Ward (Atlanta)|Seventh Ward]] (grey): established December 2, 1871 of parts of the Fourth and Fifth. Specifically from the \"junction of Houston and Pryor streets, thence through lot nineteen, between blocks three, one and two, five and six, to the city limits; thence northerly along the city limits to Peachtree Street; thence south along Peachtree Street and Pryor Street to the beginning.\" And the Fourth was extended \"from Ivy Street west to Pryor, and from Houston Street south to the railroad, and that Pryor Street shall be the line between the fourth and fifth wards, and Pryor and Peachtree streets between the fifth and seventh wards.\" This gave the red-light district to the Fourth and created a new Ward of mostly farmers and to the west, fine residences along Ivy and the east side of Peachtree.\n\n===1874===\n[[Image:Atlanta-wards-1874.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Layout of Atlanta's five wards (1874 to 1883)]]\nA new city charter was approved by [[James Milton Smith|Governor Smith]] on February 28, 1874, which reduced the number of wards back to five and created a bi-cameral council of two councilmen from each ward and a second body of three at-large aldermen was established.\nEach year one of the aldermen would be up for election and during his last year in office would serve as president of the other body.\nThey acted separately on finances but together for all other business.\n\nThe new ward layout was as follows:\n*[[First Ward (Atlanta)|First Ward]] (yellow) was bounded by [[Western & Atlantic Railroad]], Foundry St, south around the city limits to modern [[Peachtree Street]]\n*[[Second Ward (Atlanta)|Second Ward]] (red) was bounded by the [[Georgia Railroad]], Whitehall south to city limits then north-east to McDonough (Capital Ave) and up to the railroad\n*[[Third Ward (Atlanta)|Third Ward]] (green) was bounded by Butler (Jesse Hill Dr) and McDonough Streets south to the city limits north-east to Georgia RR, then west to Butler\n*[[Fourth Ward (Atlanta)|Fourth Ward]] (blue) from Pryor and tracks east on Georgia RR to city limits then north west to West Peachtree and south to origin.\n*[[Fifth Ward (Atlanta)|Fifth Ward]] (purple) from Pryor and tracks north-east to Peachtree, then West Peachtree to city limits, south-west to Foundry and W&A RR and east to origin\n\n===1883===\n[[Image:Atlanta-wards-1883.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Layout of Atlanta's six wards (1883 to 1894)]]\n\nOn November 5, 1883 a [[Sixth Ward (Atlanta)|Sixth Ward]] (beige) was carved out of the Fourth and Fifth Wards.\nIts boundaries started at Butler and the [[Georgia Railroad|GRR]] (today's Grady Hospital) north to [[North Avenue (Atlanta)|North Ave]] at Myrtle St, then up Myrtle to the city limit at 3rd St.\nFollow the arc of the city limit to Williams, south to Cain (International) then James (Church) to Forsyth south to the tracks then east on the tracks to origin.\nThis separated the wealthy Peachtree corridor from the other parts of north Atlanta. (Garrett Vol II, p.&nbsp;53\u201354)\n\n===1889===\nExpansion of city limits to one and three-quarters radius from [[Atlanta Union Station (1871)|union depot]].<ref name=gis/>\n\n===1894===\nWhen [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]] was annexed into the city in 1894, it became a new [[Seventh Ward (Atlanta)|Seventh Ward]].\n\n===1904===\n{{convert|822|acre|ha}} annexed - the southern part of what is now Midtown was already within the 1889 limits, but in 1904 the city annexes most of the rest of what is now Midtown: this is an area bounded by the 1889 circular city limits on the south, and West Peachtree St. on the west, stretching north up to but not including Ansley Park (roughly 6th to 16th Streets), Piedmont Park, the remainder of Historic Midtown east to what is now the [[BeltLine]]. this includes a strip of what is now the [[Old Fourth Ward]] between the 1889 limits and the BeltLine.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=126 City of Atlanta annexation database, Case ANX-1904-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1905===\nFurther expansion of the city limits was part of a long effort.\n\nIn October 1897 [[Frank P. Rice]] drove a failed proposal to annex [[Pittsburgh (Atlanta)|Pittsburgh]], [[Reynoldstown]], [[Bellwood (Atlanta)|Bellwood]], and what was then called \"north Atlanta\".<ref>[\"Suburbs will not be annexed now: The Rice measure tabled by Council yesterday afternoon\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', October 27, 1897]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/atlantayesterday00horn/atlantayesterday00horn_djvu.txt John R. Hornady, \"Atlanta yesterday, today and tomorrow\", 1922]</ref>\n\n\"North Atlanta\" was defined at the time roughly as today's [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]], [[Georgia Tech]], and [[English Avenue]]:<ref>[\"Outside Folks Hot After Rice\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', October 24, 1897]</ref>\n* today's Midtown between Myrtle St. in the [[Midtown Historic District (Atlanta, Georgia)|Midtown Historic District]] and Cherry St., now inside the Georgia Tech campus, as far north as 14th St (then called Wilson Ave.)\n* most of what is now the Georgia Tech campus, south of what was then 5th Street\n* the area west of Georgia Tech, south of Jefferson St., as far west as Ashby St. (now Lowery Blvd.), including today's English Avenue neighborhood\n\nIn 1902 a special committee made a new proposal to annex those areas as well as \"Bonnie Brae\", [[Copenhill]], and the \"St. Charles Avenue\" area (in today's [[Virginia Highland]]). By then, \"north Atlanta\" was being referred to as \"Peachtree\".<ref>[\"New Limits Outlined for Greater Atlanta\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', Apr. 30, 1902]</ref>\n\nIn 1905, the [[Eighth Ward (Atlanta)|Eighth Ward]] was added. An act of the [[Georgia General Assembly]] was enacted on August 3, 1904 which designated the area from then current city limits (at 6th St and West Peachtree), north to 15th St, then east to Piedmont Ave, then northeast to [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]] (basically follow Piedmont to the [[Ansley Park]] area), then southwardly along the railway the limits. The act also took part of the Sixth Ward north of North Ave. into the new Eighth Ward.\n\n===1909===\nOn January 1, 1909, a Ninth Ward was formed out of just annexed [[Copenhill]], part of [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]], [[Edgewood (Atlanta)|Edgewood]], [[Reynoldstown]] and [[East Atlanta]]. Edgewood alone had had its own city government before the annexation.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7qpif6-Z5o4C&pg=PA539 ''Atlanta and Environs: A Chronicle of Its People and Events, 1880s-1930s'', Franklin M. Garrett, p.539]</ref>\n\n===1910===\n\n====Annexations====\nAnnexation of {{convert|3510|acre|ha sqmi|2|lk=on}} to the north and west:<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=118 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1910-004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210173311/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=118 |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref><ref name=annexationmap>[http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/MapsTest/id/155/rec/126 Annexation Map of Atlanta, City of Atlanta, revised 1981] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814210044/http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/MapsTest/id/155/rec/126 |date=2013-08-14 }}</ref>\n*[[Ansley Park]] and most of [[Sherwood Forest (Atlanta)|Sherwood Forest]]\n*[[Peachtree Street]] from 15h street north to Palisades Road in southern [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]]\n*the area that is now the [[Georgia Tech]] campus that was not already part of the city, including the [[Hemphill Avenue]] neighborhood\n*[[Bankhead (Atlanta)|Bankhead]] east of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] line\n*Remainder of [[English Avenue]] (northern part) that was not already part of the city\n*[[Washington Park (Atlanta)|Washington Park]]\n*What is now [[Mozley Park]], then called Battle Hill\n*Ashview Heights\n*remainder of today's [[West End (Atlanta)|West End]] (western part) that was not already part of the city\n*most of [[Westview (Atlanta)|Westview]]\n\nAnnexation of {{convert|2011|acre|ha sqmi|2|lk=on}} including the town of [[Oakland City (Atlanta)|Oakland City]] and from the previous city limits south to the [[BeltLine]]: [[Adair Park]], most of [[Pittsburgh (Atlanta)|Pittsburgh]], southern [[Summerhill (Atlanta)|Summerhill]], southern/eastern edges of [[Grant Park (Atlanta)|Grant Park]] neighborhood.<ref name=annexationmap/><ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=119 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1910-003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210172412/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=119 |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n\nAnnexation of the blocks surrounding Brown Park (now Brownwood Park) in [[East Atlanta]] - Moreland east to Stokesland and Glenwood south to the current city limits.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=120 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1910-002]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====New Tenth Ward====\nA new Tenth Ward was created. The eastern boundary was McDaniel Street. The southwestern boundary was Whitehall Street to the Central of Georgia Railroad, and from there along the railroad to a point just south of the BeltLine. From there, the boundary ran due west to a prolongation of Holderness Street south of the BeltLine, and from there southwest to the junction of Campbellton and Utoy roads. Then due east along the north boundary of Fort McPherson to the Central of Georgia Railroad. Then south along that railway line to a point between Osborne and Astor avenues, then east to Sylvan Road, then north to the BeltLine, then east to McDaniel Street.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ByTgAtilbi4C&pg=PA558 ''Atlanta and Environs: A Chronicle of Its People and Events, 1880s-1930s'', Franklin M. Garrett p.558]</ref>\n\nThis included:\n*New territory from the annexations including Oakland City\n*Territory from the Second Ward west of McDaniel Street\n*Territory from the Seventh Ward east of the Central of Georgia Railroad\n\n===1919===\nEleventh Ward created from part of the Ninth Ward (area south of the [[Georgia Railroad and Banking Company|Georgia railroad line]]) and from part of the Third Ward. The new ward corresponds to East Atlanta, Ormewood Park, and other adjacent areas.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Fxg4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA834 ''Acts passed by the General Assembly of Georgia, 1919'', p.834]</ref>\n\n===1922===\n*[[Kirkwood (Atlanta)|Kirkwood]]<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=107 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-006]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> annexed ({{convert|975|acre|ha sqmi|1}})\n*North part of [[Virginia-Highland]] and south part of [[Morningside/Lenox Park]] annexed ({{convert|858|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=110 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-003]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=111 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-002]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*[[Ormewood Park]] annexed ({{convert|482|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=112 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1922-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1923===\nIn June 1923 there was a failed movement to annex [[College Park, Georgia|College Park]], [[East Point, Georgia|East Point]], and [[Hapeville, Georgia|Hapeville]].<ref>[http://www.fold3.com/image/#25|102033847 \"Steps are taken for annexation of three suburbs\", ''Atlanta Constitution'', June 30, 1923, p.1]</ref>\n\n===1928===\n*[[East Lake (Atlanta)|East Lake]] annexed ({{convert|717|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=84 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1928-004]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> as the 12th ward. \n*[[Chosewood Park]] annexed. ({{convert|626|acre|ha sqmi|1}})<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=87 Atlanta annexation database, case ANX-1928-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1929===\nA Thirteenth Ward was created as the section of the Ninth Ward north of St. Charles and east of the [[Belt Line (Atlanta)|Belt Line]] to the west side of Briarcliff and north the corporate limits. (most of today's [[Virginia-Highland]])\n\n===1937===\nOn March 14, 1935, the legislature reduced the number of wards from 13 to 6 and the thirty-nine member city council is cut to eighteen members effective January 1, 1937. The wards were combined as such:\n*First: old 2nd & 3rd (south from Central RR to Grant Park)\n*Second: old 11th & 12th (southeast: Ormewood, East Atlanta and East Lake)\n*Third: old 1st, 5th & 6th (northwest from Central RR around to three blocks east of Peachtree)\n*Fourth: old 7th & 10th (from West End to Oakland City)\n*Fifth: old 4th & 8th (from Georgia RR up to Piedmont Park and Ansley west of the [[Belt Line (Atlanta)|Belt Line]])\n*Sixth: old 9th & 13th (everything east of the Belt Line and north of Georgia RR: Inman Park, Druid Hills, etc.)<ref>Garrett, Vol. II, p.927</ref>\n\n===1952===\n[[File:Atlanta annexation 1952.jpg|thumb|300px|1952 annexation]]\nIn 1951, after a failed 1947 referendum and two other failed attempts, the state legislature passed a \"Plan of Improvement\" by which on Jan. 1, 1952, the city annexed {{convert|51470|acre|ha sqmi|1|lk=on}} in  [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], Adams Park, [[Neighborhoods of Atlanta#Southwestern Atlanta|Southwest Atlanta]] & [[Lakewood Heights (Atlanta)|Lakewood]].<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=66 City of Atlanta Annexation database, Case ANX-1952-005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210173458/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=66 |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref> This was by far the largest expansion in Atlanta's history, tripling the size of the city to {{convert|118|mi2|km2}} and adding 100,000 residents. This helped spread the burden of providing public services by adding to the base a large group of mostly more affluent residents. The annexation was viewed as a triumph of [[William Hartsfield|Mayor Hartsfield]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_WuW4GAUg9EC&lpg=PA71&dq=buckhead%20annexed%20square%20miles&pg=PA86 | title=William Berry Hartsfield: Mayor of Atlanta| isbn=9780820335445| last1=Martin| first1=Harold H.| date=May 2010}}</ref>\n\nAtlanta would in the 1970s again try, but without success, to repeat the process by state legislation to annex what is now [[Sandy Springs, Georgia|Sandy Springs]] to Atlanta.<ref>[http://www.sandysprings.com/history.aspx ''City of Sandy Springs'', \"History\"]</ref>\n\n===1953===\nAnnexation of [[Ben Hill (Atlanta)|Ben Hill]], [[Greenbriar (Atlanta)|Greenbriar]] and other adjacent areas in far southwestern Atlanta.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=59 City of Atlanta annexation database Case ID ANX-1953-001]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===1954===\nThe ward system is ended. No longer a bicameral body, only a board of six aldermen with a Vice-Mayor serving as president of the board. All positions were elected citywide. (For post-ward setup, see [[Political structure of Atlanta]]).\n\n===Annexations since 1953===\nSince 1953, multiple small annexations (and deannexations) to the City of Atlanta have occurred, in two periods from 1954-1979 and 2003-2010. No annexations took place from 1979 to 2003.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?page=1, 2, 3, 4, 5 City of Atlanta GIS Annexations database]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMultiple small areas adjacent to southwestern Atlanta were annexed including [[Midwest Cascade]], Cascade Glen, and the Horseshoe Community.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?page=2 |title=City of Atlanta GIS Annexations database |access-date=2011-11-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425231716/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?page=2 |archive-date=2012-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Sandtown, Georgia|Sandtown]]'s 2007 petition for annexation was put on hold.<ref>[http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=2 Atlanta annexations database, case ANX-2006-006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413155440/http://gis.atlantaga.gov/apps/annex/index.php?a=view&recid=2 |date=April 13, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThese annexations added a few thousand residents, and approximately three square miles, including areas mostly in the southwest of the city, but also small parcels in the east and north of the city.\n\n===Emory University and Centers for Disease Control annexation===\nIn December 2017, the Atlanta City Council approved an annexation request by [[Emory University]], the [[Centers for Disease Control]], [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta - Egleston Hospital]], and other contiguous property owners in the [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]] neighborhood of [[Dekalb County, Georgia|Dekalb County]]. The annexation was effective January 1, 2018.<ref name=NiesseEmoryannexed/> In June 2017 the university leadership formally petitioned the City of Atlanta to annex it.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stafford, Leon|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/emory-university-formally-files-petition-become-part-atlanta/KkN3nSaOPuSOKPGICIxnwJ/|title=Emory University formally files petition to become part of Atlanta|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-06-27|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> To comply with the requirement that an annexed area be adjacent to the existing city limits, the university purchased a residence partially within the then-city limits.<ref>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/path-for-emory-university-join-atlanta-runs-through-backyard/7JRjnX8DZC9KbdXdwjzkXJ/|title=Path for Emory University to join Atlanta runs through a backyard|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-03-03|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> The city government also entered into a settlement with the [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]] government to settle a dispute, paving the way for the annexation.<ref>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|author2=Leon Stafford|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/deal-between-atlanta-and-dekalb-clears-way-for-city-expansion-emory/OVby4dKuzmPSh8W4yQlcyO/|title=Deal between Atlanta and DeKalb clears way for city\u2019s expansion to Emory|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-09-26|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nDue to the taxable revenue involved, there was a dispute over whether the area would remain in the [[DeKalb County School District]] or transition to [[Atlanta Public Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Niesse, Mark|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/emory-annexation-won-finished-time-for-atlanta-elections/5XmFt1qUhAAH4gAn8yF5QM/|title=9 students and $2.3M stand in the way of Emory\u2019s annexation to Atlanta|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2017-10-16|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> In 2016 Emory University made a statement that \"Annexation of Emory into the City of Atlanta will not change school districts, since neighboring communities like [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]] will still be self-determining regarding annexation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.emory.edu/stories/2016/08/upress_atlanta_annexation_statement/index.html|title=\nEmory University statement on possible annexation|publisher=[[Emory University]]|date=2016-08-19|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> The annexed area ultimately went to APS,<ref name=NiesseEmoryannexed/> and as part of a 2019 settlement Emory would help establish school-based clinics for DeKalb schools.<ref>{{cite web|author=McCray, Vanessa|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/aps-dekalb-annexation-deal-could-pay-for-six-school-health-clinics/5mbGjr9WelTTKnoIUmArUJ/?fbclid=IwAR01FkInaRhB_qxC677slVPgDIMKYSoXUdFHbTW1PX8iaGJfwF-fX3gj3g4|title=APS, DeKalb annexation deal could pay for six school health clinics|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=2019-12-10|accessdate=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | last=Garrett | first=Franklin Miller | authorlink=Franklin Garrett | year=1969 | title=Atlanta and Environs: A Chronicle of Its People and Events | publisher=University of Georgia Press | location=Georgia | isbn=0-8203-0263-5}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060319162755/http://apps.atlantaga.gov/citycoul/history.htm City Council history]\n*Stone, Clarence N., ''Regime Politics Governing Atlanta: 1946\u20131988'', 1989, University Press of Kansas\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130814210044/http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/MapsTest/id/155/rec/126 Detailed map of Atlanta annexations by City of Atlanta at Georgia State Library digital collections]\n**[https://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/digital/collection/atlmaps/id/155 Annexation Map of Atlanta from the 1980s]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Atlanta history}}\n\n[[Category:History of Atlanta|Ward System]]\n[[Category:Government of Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Geography of Atlanta]]\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEmory University and Centers for Disease Control annexation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atlanta_annexations_and_wards"}
