ategory:KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:January 1879 events]]\n", "name_user": "JuliusPepperwoodExCopExMarine", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrelude", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Isandlwana"}
{"title_page": "BritBox", "text_new": "{{short description|Internet media streaming and video on demand service broadcasting British TV}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name = BritBox\n| logo = BritBox logo.svg\n| company_type = [[Joint venture]]\n| founder = {{plainlist|\n* [[BBC]]\n* [[ITV plc|ITV]]\n}}\n| industry = Entertainment, Internet\n| area_served = {{flatlist|\n* [[United Kingdom]]\n* [[United States]]\n* [[Canada]]}}\n| products = {{flatlist|\n* Streaming media\n* Video on demand\n}}\n| services = {{flatlist|\n* Film production\n* Film distribution\n* Television production\n}}\n| divisions = North America <br>UK Streaming\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| alexa = \n| registration = Required\n| foundation = \n| owner = BritBox LLC<br>([[Northern America|North America]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britbox.com/us/privacy|title=BritBox|website=www.britbox.com}}</ref> <br> BritBox SVOD Limited ([[United Kingdom|UK]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britbox.co.uk/privacy|title=BritBox - BritBox UK Privacy Notice|website=www.britbox.co.uk}}</ref>\n| parent = [[BBC Studios]] (10%) &<br> [[ITV plc]] (90%)\n| location = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.britbox.com}} (US/CAN) <br> {{URL|https://www.britbox.co.uk}} (UK)\n| num_users = 1,000,000 subscribers ([[Northern America|United States & Canada]])\n| language = English\n| type = {{plainlist|\n*[[Over-the-top media services|OTT platform]]}}\n| key_people = {{plainlist|\n* Soumya Sriraman <br><small>(President, North America)\n}}\n| launch_date = {{plainlist|\n* {{Start date and age|2017|3|7|df=y}}  <small>([[United States]])</small>\n* {{Start date and age|2018|2|14|df=y}}  <small>([[Canada]])</small>\n* {{Start date and age|2019|11|7|df=y}}  <small>([[United Kingdom]])</small>}}\n| current_status = Active\n}}\n\n'''BritBox''' (stylised '''britbox''') is a [[Digital media|digital]] [[video]] [[Subscription business model|subscription service]] created by [[BBC]] and [[ITV plc]], serving the [[United Kingdom]], [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=\":6\">[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/britbox-lands-in-canada-sure-to-be-a-major-disruptor-in-tv-landscape/article38016368/ \"BritBox lands in Canada, sure to be a major disruptor in ever-shifting TV landscape\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', February 18, 2018.</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britbox.com/us/help|title=BritBox|website=Britbox.com|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>  It is focused on [[Television in the United Kingdom|British television series]] and [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|films]], mainly featuring current and past series and films supplied from the main UK [[Public broadcasting|public service broadcasters]] (the [[BBC]], [[ITV plc|ITV]], [[Channel Four Television Corporation|Channel 4]] and [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]). BritBox is said to feature the biggest collection of British box-sets available in one place, with more original programming set to be available from 2020. BritBox's focus on British content has led to the service being described as a 'niche streaming service' in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/niche-streaming-services-thrive-land-giants/|title=How niche streaming services thrive in the land of giants|last=Peterson|first=Tim|date=2019-10-24|website=Digiday|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nBritBox's launch in the United States was announced in December 2016, with it launching on 7 March 2017.<ref name=\"thr-britbox\">{{cite web|title=BBC Worldwide, ITV SVOD Venture BritBox Launches With $6.99 Monthly Price|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bbc-worldwide-itv-svod-venture-britbox-launches-699-monthly-price-983887|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref> It launched in Canada on 14 February 2018<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/britbox-launches-canada|title=BritBox Launches in Canada|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref><ref name=\"iphoneincanada.ca\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iphoneincanada.ca/news/britbox-launch-canada/|title=BBC's BritBox Launches in Canada: British TV Streaming at $8.99/Month|date=2018-02-15|website=iPhone in Canada Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> and proposals for a UK launch were finalised on 27 February 2019, with the service launching in the United Kingdom on 7 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-50320731|title=UK TV's streaming service BritBox goes live|date=2019-11-07|access-date=2019-11-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> There are content restrictions between each platform, leading some content to be available on one platform and unavailable on another.\n\nBritBox provides new episodes to British soaps and dramas such as ''[[EastEnders]], [[Coronation Street]] and [[Emmerdale]]'', within hours of their UK broadcast via BritBox\u2019s \u2018Now\u2019 feature to North American users.\n\nIt reported a subscriber base of 250,000 within a year since launching in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/britbox-scores-250k-subscribers-just-under-a-year-after-launch-1202305109/|title=BritBox passes 250,000 subscribers|date=2018-02-28|website=Informitv.com|language=en-US|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> In 2019, 650,000 subscribers were reported from the North American platform.<ref>[https://www.choose.co.uk/news/2019/britbox-launch BritBox set for launch before end of 2019] Choose LTD 23 July 2019</ref> In 2020, the number of [[North America|North American]] subscribers increased to 1 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-03-04/by-catering-to-brit-tv-fans-britbox-reaches-1-million-north-american-subscribers|title=Helped by \u2018Father Brown,\u2019 BritBox reaches 1 million North American subscribers|last=Lee|first=Wendy|date=March 4, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Failed \"Project Kangaroo\" ===\n{{Main|Kangaroo (video on demand)}}\nThough not officially described as its successor, BritBox has been likened to an earlier attempt by UK public service broadcasters (BBC Worldwide, ITV and Channel 4) to create an online [[video-on-demand]] download service, codenamed \"''Project Kangaroo''\" in November 2007. This followed the launches of the broadcasters' own video-on-demand services.\n\nOn Wednesday, 4 February 2009, Project Kangaroo was blocked by the [[Competition Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/feb/04/project-kangaroo-blocked-by-competition-commission|title=Project Kangaroo blocked by Competition Commission|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2009-02-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-03|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nThe commission stated that the case surrounding Kangaroo was about the control of valuable UK-originated TV content. \"BBC Worldwide, ITV and Channel 4 together control the vast majority of this material, which puts them in a very strong position as wholesalers of TV content to restrict competition from other current and future providers of video-on-demand services to UK viewers,\" said Peter Freeman, the chairman of the Competition Commission, in its final report on Project Kangaroo. \"We thought viewers would benefit from better video-on-demand [VoD] services if the parties \u2013 possibly in conjunction with other new and/or already established providers of VoD \u2013 competed with each other.\"\n\nA Channel 4 spokesperson said at the time, \"This is a disproportionate remedy and a missed opportunity in the further development of British broadcasting.\"\n\nAfter the planned Project Kangaroo was blocked, the system's assets were sold to transmitter firm [[Arqiva]] and this led to the development of the service [[SeeSaw (Internet television)|SeeSaw]], which operated from February 2010 to October 2011, with content from the BBC, Channel 4, and Channel 5, some of which (such as ''[[Doctor Who]]'') now appears on BritBox.\n\n=== Entry of Netflix ===\nSince the arrival of [[Netflix]], European PSBs and Media companies have started to find ways to compete with American Subscription Video on Demand services (SVODs), and many old rivalries have also been put aside in Europe and to collaborate by creating joint SVODs, such the like of BritBox but also France's Salto (backed by networks [[TF1 Group|TF1]], [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]] and [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]]), and German-based [[:de:Joyn_(Streaminganbieter)|Joyn]] (a joint venture between [[ProSiebenSat.1 Media|ProSiebenSat.1]] and [[Discovery, Inc.|Discovery]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/european-broadcasters-unite-take-netflix-global-streamers-1217336|title=A European Union of TV? Broadcasters Team to Take on Netflix and Global Streamers|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>.\n\n=== Establishment of joint venture ===\nTalks between the BBC and ITV to launch a Netflix-style streaming service took place in March 2016, with [[NBCUniversal]] also initially in the talks.\n\n==== Launch in US ====\nFollowing increased competition for the public service broadcasters from streaming giants, the BBC and ITV announced plans to create a Netflix-style TV service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/dec/13/bbc-and-itv-to-launch-britbox-on-demand-service-in-us|title=BBC and ITV to launch BritBox on-demand service in US|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2016-12-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-03|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The BBC and ITV did announce several shows they will be running on Britbox including ''New Blood'', ''Tutankhamun'', ''The Moonstone, In The Dark,'' Cold ''Feet'' and crime series ''Silent Witness'' on launch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltveurope.com/2016/12/14/bbc-itv-amc-pact-for-britbox-us-svod-service/|title=BBC, ITV, AMC pact for BritBox US SVOD service|date=2016-12-14|website=Digital TV Europe|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Launch in Canada ====\nOn 14 February 2018, BritBox launched in Canada. Soumya Sriraman, President, BritBox North America, said, \u201cWe know that Canadians have a deep affinity for British culture and the extraordinary television programs produced in the UK, so launching BritBox in Canada has always been at the top of our list. The fact that we can also, for the first time ever, premiere some of the most popular British programs and big special events such as Trooping the Colour as soon as 24 hours after their UK premiere is \u2013 hopefully \u2013 the cherry on the sundae.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/britbox-launches-canada|title=BritBox Launches in Canada|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n==== UK launch ====\nIn February 2019, it was announced that BritBox would be launched in the UK later in the year as a rival to [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47383559|title=BBC and ITV set to launch Netflix rival|date=27 February 2019|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> Journalist [[Mark Lawson]] likened the proposed project to [[BBC Worldwide]]'s previous failed platform, Project Kangaroo, which was expected to launch in 2008, and described it as \"bizarre\" and \"hugely risky\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/feb/27/britbox-this-bizarre-netflix-rival-will-surely-bomb|title=BritBox: the bizarre Netflix rival that will surely bomb|date=27 February 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> In March 2019, [[Channel 4]] confirmed interest in collaborating with the [[BBC]] and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].<ref name=\"Channel 4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a26751093/channel-4-boss-confirms-interest-joining-britbox-alongside-bbc-itv/|title=Channel 4 boss confirms interest in joining BritBox alongside BBC and ITV|last1=Mehmedova|first1=Filiz|date=7 March 2019|publisher=[[DigitalSpy]]|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref> Currently, ''McMafia'', ''Last Tango in Halifax'', ''Les Mis\u00e9rables'' and the sitcom ''Gavin & Stacey'' have been confirmed to be available on the UK version.<ref name=\"Channel 4\" />\n\nIn July 2019, the BBC and ITV announced they had signed an agreement to launch BritBox in the UK in the last quarter of 2019.<ref>[https://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/market-news/market-news-detail/ITV/14155960.html Full Stream Ahead for BritBox in UK as ITV & BBC Sign Agreement] ITV 19 July 2019</ref> \n\nOn 20 September 2019, ITV announced they had reached a deal with Viacom for Channel 5 and Comedy Central UK content.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/britbox/press-releases/channel-5-and-comedy-central-join-britbox-line|title=Channel 5 and Comedy Central join BritBox line-up|website=Press Centre}}</ref> This was followed by an announcement on 27 September that Samsung TVs, Freeview Play and YouView would be the first distribution platforms <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/britbox/press-releases/britbox-confirms-first-wave-distribution-partners|title=BritBox confirms first wave of distribution partners|website=Press Centre}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, BritBox launched its [[Beta release|\"testing phase\"]] (beta) in the United Kingdom, in which users can sign up for a free trial to have a \"snapshot of what will be there at launch\".<ref name=\"trial\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2019-10-15/britbox-releases-beta-version-free-trial/|title=Britbox releases Beta version for users to sign up to 30 day free trial|last=Carr|first=Flora|date=15 October 2019|website=Radio Times|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOne day before UK launch, on 6 November 2019, the Guardian reported that Channel 4 is to join BritBox after the two signed a 3-year deal to provide 1000+ hours of content from All 4 \"with a range of comedy, drama and non-scripted programmes from across the service, including new series, and for the first time to any streamer, an exclusive Film4 curated service featuring iconic British films\".<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"itv.com\" /> This means for the first time, all the UK's traditional channels have managed to successfully bring together programmes on a single streaming service. Channel 4 content will be available on BritBox from Spring 2020 and Film4 content later in 2020, with recently aired content being only available on BritBox 31 days after the airing of the last episode on Channel 4.<ref name=\"itv.com\" /> Channel 4 currently has not taken an equity stake in BritBox.\n\n== Ownership ==\nBritBox is a joint venture of BBC Studios and ITV plc, shown in the tagline \"by BBC & ITV\". The service in North America is owned by BritBox LLC<ref name=\":6\" />, and in the UK by BritBox SVOD Ltd<ref name=\":7\" />, joint ventures of [[BBC Studios]] and [[ITV plc]]. [[ITV plc|ITV]] owns 90% of the joint venture, with BBC Studios holding the remaining 10%, with the option of increasing their share to 25%. [[AMC Networks]], the BBC's partner on its US cable channel [[BBC America]], has a non-voting minority stake in the U.S. service, since they have a vested stake in RLJ Entertainment (who owns a rival British TV service [[Acorn TV]].) and their own [[Shudder (streaming service)|Shudder]] SVOD service.<ref name=\"thr-britboxcorrie\">{{cite web|title='Coronation Street' Episodes Now Available on BritBox a Day After UK. Debut|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/coronation-street-episodes-available-britbox-a-day-uk-debut-1001611|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/bbc-itv-streaming-service-u-s-britbox-1201940621/|title=BBC, ITV Partner for U.S. Streaming Service BritBox, AMC Networks to Take Minority Stake|last=Schwindt|first=Oriana|date=13 December 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=23 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Channel 4 and Channel 5 currently have no equity share in any of the platforms.\n\n==Content==\n\n=== Original programmes ===\nIn September 2017, BritBox released a reconstruction of the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' story ''[[The Wheel in Space]]'' using the surviving episodes and reconstruction using [[Tele-snaps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1030062/the-doctor-who-fans-saving-the-episodes-once-thought-lost-to-the-mists-of-time-and-space/|title=The \"Doctor Who\" fans saving the episodes once thought lost to the mists of time and space|first=Ashley|last=Rodriguez|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref> In July 2018, ''[[The Bletchley Circle: San Francisco]]'' made its debut, the first original drama series in which BritBox held a direct production role.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/the-bletchley-circle-san-francisco-britbox-offers-first-glimpse-of-its-first-original-set-to-launch-in-july-1202402745|title='The Bletchley Circle: San Francisco': BritBox Offers First Glimpse Of Its First Original, Set To Launch In July|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Peter|last=White|date=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nMore original content is set to be commissioned and produced for 2020, following the platform's UK launch, with the [https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/ BBC Media Centre] stating \"The first new show is expected to be commissioned soon and will be available to BritBox viewers from 2020\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2019/britbox-agreement Full stream ahead for BritBox in UK as ITV and BBC sign agreement] BBC Media Centre 19 July 2019</ref> The goal is to offer exclusive content only available on BritBox, rather than BBC and ITV's UK VOD services [[BBC iPlayer]] and [[ITV Hub]]. The annual budget for original programmes will be in the tens of millions of pounds according to [[BBC News]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-49037855 BritBox: ITV and BBC set out plans for new streaming service] BBC News 19 July 2019</ref>\n\nITV has pledged to invest up to \u00a365m in the joint venture over the next two years, and the BBC has said their pledge would be in the \"tens of millions\".<ref name=\"radiotimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2019-11-07/britbox-streaming-site-explained/|title=What is BritBox? BBC and ITV's answer to Netflix in the UK|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n====Drama====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Genre\n! Premiere\n! Series/episodes\n! Status\n|-\n|''[[The Bletchley Circle: San Francisco]]''\n|[[Crime]] [[wikt:mystery|mystery]]\n|{{sort|2018-07-25|25 July 2018}}\n|{{sort|18|1 series, 8 episodes}}\n| Renewed\n|-\n\n|}\n\n=== Film and television deals ===\nIn addition to containing the catalogues of BBC and ITV television''',''' BritBox includes content from [[Channel Four Television Corporation|Channel 4]] (including [[Film4 Productions|Film4]])''',''' and [[ViacomCBS International Media Networks Europe|ViacomCBS]] through the UK channels [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] and [[Comedy Central (British TV channel)|Comedy Central]].\n\nOther potential networks to offer content or ownership of BritBox include: [[NBCUniversal]] (owned by [[Comcast]]) and [[BT Consumer|BT]]. Such collaboration would greatly increase BritBox's catalogue and financial resources when competing with other streaming platforms like [[Netflix]], [[Disney+]] and [[Amazon Prime|Prime Video]]. BT and NBCUniversal were reportedly in early talks with BritBox, but the progress of the talks have yet to be stated, with NBCUniversal launching their own streaming service, [[Peacock (streaming service)|Peacock]] in the US in 2020<ref>[https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/nbcuniversal-streaming-service-details-1203108034 What We Know About NBCUniversal\u2019s Future Streaming Service] Variety 15 January 2019</ref> and its parent Comcast owning Sky's UK streaming service [[Now TV (Sky)|Now TV]], making collaboration with NBCUniversal unlikely. BT has since signed a partnership with BritBox in which the service will complement it own content.\n\nArran Tindall, Senior Vice President, Commercial & Content Distribution, Viacom International Media Networks said \u201cUnder Viacom\u2019s ownership we have significantly increased Channel 5\u2019s investment in original UK content and we\u2019re delighted to bring our popular homegrown content to an even wider audience through BritBox, alongside a selection of Comedy Central\u2019s much-loved UK programming.\u201d following the announcement that Viacom content of Channel 5 and Comedy Central UK would be joining the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/britbox/press-releases/channel-5-and-comedy-central-join-britbox-line|title=Channel 5 and Comedy Central join BritBox line-up|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nIn the early days of BritBox, Channel 4 was reportedly in talks with BritBox for a long period, ITV chief executive [[Carolyn McCall]] confirmed to ''RadioTimes.com'' that talks are \"continuing\" with Channel 4 and said that they will \"welcome Channel 4 to BritBox\".<ref>[https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2019-07-19/britbox-bbc-itv-streaming-service-launch-date-cost-programmes Everything you need to know about BritBox \u2013 BBC and ITV\u2019s answer to Netflix in the UK] Radiotimes 19 July 2019</ref> On 6 November, the Guardian reported that Channel 4 is to join BritBox, with its content expected to be available on the service from early 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/nov/06/channel-4-to-join-new-uk-streaming-platform-britbox|title=Channel 4 to join new UK streaming platform BritBox|last=editor|first=Jim Waterson Media|date=2019-11-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Channel 4, a publisher-broadcaster, must commission UK content from independent production companies and currently works with around 300 companies across the UK every year.<ref name=\"itv.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/britbox/press-releases/brand-new-uk-streaming-service-britbox-open-business-partnerships-struck-channel-4-bt|title=Brand new UK streaming service BritBox open for business. Partnerships struck with Channel 4, BT and EE|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> As such, Channel 4 potentially lacks the streaming rights to many of the shows it broadcasts. Many independent broadcasters waive these rights in order to strike more lucrative deals with larger SVODs while retaining control over their intellectual property. This would therefore potentially cause the UK platform to have differing content from the North American platform.\n\nContent co-produced between British Broadcasters and Larger SVODs like Netflix and Prime Video will not be available on all or any BritBox platforms.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/britbox-marking-classic-british-sitcoms-inappropriate-2566718|title=BritBox will mark some classic British sitcoms as \"inappropriate\"|last=Warner|first=Sam|date=2019-11-11|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> This includes shows like [[Bodyguard (British TV series)|Bodyguard]] regarding which a BritBox spokesperson said \"Can't come back home\", adding that \u201cgoing forward, [BritBox] won\u2019t licence things to Netflix and Amazon in the first place because we now have a home, a streaming service in the UK\u201d.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/britbox-netflix-itv-bbc-british-shows-removed-a9193756.html|title=The 'vast majority' of British shows will be removed from Netflix within the next year|date=2019-11-07|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC, however, makes much of its content via BBC Studios, as does ITV with ITV Studios, and in some instances for each other, so the rights to their programmes are in their control.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2019-07-19/britbox-bbc-itv-streaming-service-launch-date-cost-programmes/|title=Everything you need to know about BritBox \u2013 BBC and ITV's answer to Netflix in the UK|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Film and television deals for BritBox\n!Broadcaster\n!Content provider\n!Date joined\n!Content added\n!Contract\n!Platforms\n!Notes\n!Exceptions\n|-\n|[[BBC Studios|BBC]]\n|Archive, original programming\n|Founder\n|On launch\n|  \u2013\n|All\n|Content shared* with [[BBC iPlayer]] up to 12 months after airing\n|Co-produced content with other SVODs.\n|-\n|[[ITV Studios|ITV]]\n|Archive, original programming\n|Founder\n|On launch\n|  \u2013\n|All\n|Content shared* with [[ITV Hub]] up to 30 days after airing\n|Co-produced content with other SVODs.\n|-\n|[[Channel Four Television Corporation|Channel 4]]\n|Original programming, [[Film4 Productions|Film 4]] original films\n|6 Nov 2019\n|Spring 2020, (Film4 later in 2020) until 2023.\n|3 years\n|TBA\n|British TV box sets (otherwise available on All 4) and British films (from Film4) only, therefore collaborations (with Netflix, etc.) are likely not included Content shared* with [[All 4]] up to 31 days after airing\n|Co-produced content with other SVODs.\n|-\n|[[ViacomCBS International Media Networks Europe|ViacomCBS]]\n|[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5,]] [[Comedy Central (British TV channel)|Comedy Central UK]]\n|20 Sep 2019\n|TBA\n|\n|TBA\n|British comedies from Comedy Central only. Channel 5 Content shared* with [[My5]] up to 30 days after airing.\n|Non-British Content\n|-\n|[[NBCUniversal]]\n|  \u2013\n|Unconfirmed\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|  \u2013\n|Talks didn't progress\n|  \u2013\n|-\n|[[BT Consumer|BT]] (Content)\n|Partnership\n|7 Nov 2019\n|No content\n|  \u2013\n|  \u2013\n|BritBox will become available to the millions of customers who subscribe to its pay-TV service, which broadcasts programming such as Champions League football<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/nov/07/britbox-uk-networks-plan-to-tackle-netflix-amazon-and-apple-tv|title=BritBox: UK networks' plan to tackle Netflix, Amazon and Apple TV+|last=correspondent|first=Mark Sweney Media business|date=2019-11-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n|  \u2013\n|-\n|[[Endemol Shine Group|Endemol Shine International]]\n|Distribution rights\n|16 Oct 2019\n|TBA\n|  \u2013\n|US, Canada\n|<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/10/16/britbox-links-with-endemol-shine-kew-media-distribution-for-north-america/|title=BritBox links with Endemol Shine, Kew Media Distribution for North America|date=2019-10-16|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n|  \u2013\n|-\n|Kew Media Distribution\n|Distribution rights\n|16 Oct 2019\n|TBA\n|  \u2013\n|US, Canada\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|  \u2013\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> after airing, not all content is expected to be on BritBox during the stated time frame.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Non-entertainment deals\n!Collaborator\n!Service provided\n!Date announced\n!Available in\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[BT Consumer|BT]] (Consumer)\n|Products\n|7 Nov 2019\n|UK\n|\"[BT] to create a range of products and offers that feature access to BritBox for millions of customers across its brands and services\", more information in coming months.\n|-\n|[[EE Limited|EE]]\n|Exclusive mobile partner\n|7 Nov 2019\n|UK\n|More information in coming months.\n|}\n\n=== Excluded content ===\n''This may not apply to all platforms.''\n\n==== 'Inappropriate' content ====\nA big part of the BritBox catalogue is the extensive archives of the public service broadcasters, BritBox faces the challenge of hosting content which contains outdated stereotypes and opinions. In response to this, BritBox has announced that it would not include classic homegrown series that are deemed to be inappropriate for modern audiences.\n\nBritBox bosses have said a range of older shows, such as the BBC's ''[[Till Death Us Do Part]]'' and ''[[It Ain't Half Hot Mum]]'', as well as ITV's ''[[Love Thy Neighbour (1972 TV series)|Love Thy Neighbour]]'', will not appear on the service because of content deemed racist or otherwise unacceptable.<ref name=\"TuckerHudson\">{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Grant|last2=Hudson|first2=Jack|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/britbox-opens-up-racist-doctor-who-can-of-worms-kv9pt68x5|title=BritBox opens up 'racist Doctor Who' can of worms|work=The Sunday Times|date=8 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Reemah Sakaan, the senior ITV executive responsible for launching the subscription video-on-demand service, said \u201cWe also recomply everything that goes on to BritBox [with modern TV viewing standards]. There\u2019s also the ability to create bespoke warnings around key programming.\u201d\n\nSakaan confirmed that ''Till Death Us Do Part'', first aired on [[BBC One|BBC1]] in 1965, which features the bigoted character [[Alf Garnett]], and ITV's 1970s series ''Love Thy Neighbour'', a sitcom about a [[West Indian]] couple who move next door to a [[White British]] couple, will not appear on the service. Some individual episodes of some shows that appear on BritBox such as BBC's ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'', ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'' and ''[[Doctor Who]]'' serial from the original run (''[[The Talons of Weng-Chiang]]'', 1977) are also deemed problematic. In the ''Doctor Who'' serial, people of Chinese extraction are termed \"inscrutable Chinks\" and an English actor performs in \"yellowface\". However, it is understood that no ''Fawlty Towers'' episodes will be cut from the service but will run with warnings of offensive language instead. The ''Doctor Who'' serial from 1977 has a warning attached indicating \"Contains stereotypes that some may find offensive.\"<ref name=\"TuckerHudson\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/nov/07/britbox-uk-networks-plan-to-tackle-netflix-amazon-and-apple-tv|title=BritBox: 'inappropriate' classic UK TV shows to be kept off service|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2019-11-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-13|last2=Waterson|first2=Jim|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-exclusive deals ===\nThe sale of rights to BBC and Channel 5 content has caused some reporters to be wary of BritBox's viability as a platform for new content, due to deals with larger SVODs to exclusively stream newer BBC content and non-exclusive deals with Sky and Now TV to access Channel 5 box sets.<ref name=\"Amaya\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.comicon.com/2019/08/01/hbo-max-gets-doctor-who-and-other-bbc-series-in-new-streaming-deal/|title=HBO Max Gets Doctor Who And Other BBC Series In New Streaming Deal|last=Amaya|first=Erik|date=2019-08-01|website=COMICON|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> However, many BBC Studios' deals have given licences to some of its content to many other SVODs on a non-exclusive basis. With newer or co-produced series more likely to be exclusive to certain SVODs. Whereas Sky already has existing deals with not only Channel 5, but Channel 4 and the BBC to have certain box sets on their Sky and Now TV platforms in the UK.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-12-07/sky-and-now-tv-looking-to-rival-britbox-as-they-bag-channel-5-shows/|title=Sky and NOW TV looking to rival BritBox as they bag Channel 5 shows|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n==== BBC Studios & HBO Max ====\nThe 11 series of 2005 revival and future series 13 and 14 of Doctor Who will be exclusive to stream on [[HBO Max]] in the US, following a deal between the two, on 1 August 2019.<ref name=\"Amaya\" /> Other content from BBC Studios such as ''[[The Honourable Woman]]'', ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]'', ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', and the British version of ''[[The Office (British TV series)|The Office]]'' would be available on HBO Max on a non-exclusive basis, meaning they would potentially be also available on BritBox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/08/02/hbo-max-scores-major-licensing-coup-for-bbc-content/|title=HBO Max scores major licensing coup for BBC content|date=2019-08-02|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==== BBC Studios & Discovery ====\nOn 1 April 2019, a 10-year content partnership was agreed between BBC Studios and [[Discovery, Inc.|Discovery]], which will see Discovery become the exclusive global home of the BBC's landmark natural history programs including the ''Planet Earth'', ''Blue Planet'' and ''Life'' franchises for SVOD. The ''Dynasties'' series, hosted by Sir David Attenborough, is included in the deal, as are future BBC-commissioned landmark series. This deal applies Worldwide except the UK, [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and [[Greater China]], meaning such series may be unavailable on BritBox platforms outside the United Kingdom. Upcoming co-produced content between Discovery and BBC Studios would be exclusive to Discovery's upcoming streaming platform outside the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/07/03/exclusive-bbc-studios-reveals-impact-of-discovery-deal-on-catch-up-rights/|title=Exclusive: BBC Studios reveals impact of Discovery deal on catch-up rights|date=2019-07-03|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/01/bbc-discovery-confirm-uktv-channels-break-up-svod-plans/|title=BBC, Discovery confirm UKTV channels break-up, SVOD plans|date=2019-04-01|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\nThe Discovery deal includes around 500 hours of non-exclusive content, which will still be available on other streaming services. A BBC Studios spokesperson told TBI that the relationship with Discovery is \u201cvery significant and important but it is not 100% exclusive on all titles in all regions and is therefore able to co-exist alongside regional deals of this type\u201d, following BBC Studios' deal to provide factual content to Greek telco [[OTE]]\u2019s pay-TV service [[Cosmote TV]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/17/bbc-studios-cosmote-svod-deal-signals-post-discovery-licensing-plans/|title=BBC Studios, Cosmote SVOD deal signals post-Discovery licensing plans|date=2019-04-17|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>.\n\n== Platforms ==\n\n=== Content restrictions between platforms ===\nThe list of available programmes differs between the Canada, UK and US platforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britbox.com/ca/help#do-you-offer-the-same-shows-in-the-us-and-canada|title=Help & Support: Do you offer the same shows in the US and Canada?|website=Britbox.com|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref>  For example, BritBox carries ''[[Coronation Street]]'' in the US but not in Canada, where the corresponding rights have long been held by [[CBC Television]]. Meanwhile, in the UK, TV shows, especially produced by independent production companies (like the BBC show ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'') may appear on the UK BritBox, as the BBC or ITV have the domestic broadcasting rights, but may not be available on BritBox elsewhere, due to the independent production companies giving international rights to services like [[Netflix]]. This means that depending on whether the BBC and ITV owns only the domestic rights, programmes on UK BritBox may not also be available on its American and Canadian platforms.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\" /> Alternatively, shows like ''[[Living the Dream (British TV series)|Living the Dream]]'' may not appear on the UK BritBox, as it is broadcast by [[Sky UK|Sky]] and available on Sky's streaming service [[Now TV (Sky)|Now TV]] in the UK, but currently appears on the US BritBox.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47389420 Will the BBC and ITV's BritBox be a hit or a flop?] BBC News 27 February 2019</ref>\n\nBBC and ITV content currently on other streaming services are likely to be exclusive to BritBox once the other SVOD licences expire, therefore potentially leading to harmony in programming between the platforms.<ref name=\"radiotimes.com\" /> Any original content produced for BritBox is set to be exclusively on BritBox.\n\nContent co-produced between British Broadcasters and Larger SVODs, like Netflix and Prime Video, will not be available on all or any BritBox platforms.,<ref name=\":4\" /> these include shows like ''[[Bodyguard (British TV series)|Bodyguard]]'' in which a BritBox Spokesperson said \"can't come back home\", and who added that \"going forward, we [BritBox] won\u2019t licence things to Netflix and Amazon in the first place because we now have a home, a streaming service in the UK\",<ref name=\":5\" /> they also added that in response to not licensing to other SVODs, since its focus is on UK-produced series, the platform would not compete to acquire the rights to US or international shows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/majority-of-british-tv-shows-on-netflix-will-be-axed-from-platform-in-the-next-year-2565707|title=Majority of British shows on Netflix will move to BritBox in next 12 months|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=2019-11-07|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nRecently aired or current shows made for the BBC, ITV, Channel 5 and Channel 4 terrestrially in the United Kingdom, would appear on their VOD services, [[BBC iPlayer]], [[ITV Hub]], [[My5]] and [[All 4]] respectively before BritBox. These shows would then move to BritBox at a later date, then be exclusive to BritBox once the shows have expired on the terrestrial VOD,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> which is 30 days for ITV Hub and My5, 31 days for All 4 and 12 months for BBC iPlayer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-08-01/bbc-gets-go-ahead-to-show-programmes-for-12-months-on-iplayer/|title=BBC gets go ahead to show programmes for 12 months on iPlayer|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\nNew content not made exclusively for BritBox, but for the BBC for example, may not be available on BritBox platforms outside the UK, due to deals struck with other SVODs such as HBO Max and Discovery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/04/01/bbc-and-discovery-team-up-on-a-new-streaming-service-focused-on-factual-programming/|title=BBC and Discovery team up on a new streaming service focused on factual programming|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nBritBox's launch in the United States was announced in December 2016, it launched on 7 March 2017.<ref name=\"thr-britbox\" />\n\n==== Initial programmes on U.S. launch ====\nAmong the shows offered upon BritBox's initial launch, were the '''US premieres of ''[[New Blood (TV series)|New Blood]]''''' and '''''[[Tutankhamun (miniseries)|Tutankhamun]]'''''. In '''addition''', other episodes of new programmes available on the service include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Genre\n!Original network\n!Available platforms\n!Status\n!Notes\n|-\n|''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n|[[Medical drama]]\n|BBC\n|U.S, Canada\n|Renewed\n|<ref name=\"engadget\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/07/bbc-itv-britbox-streaming-service-launch/|title=BBC and ITV's 'BritBox' streaming service arrives in the US|last=Summers|first=Nick|date=3 July 2017|work=Endgadget UK|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Coronation Street]]''\n|[[Soap opera]]\n|ITV\n|U.S, Canada\n|Renewed\n|\n|-\n|''[[EastEnders]]''\n|Soap opera\n|BBC\n|U.S, Canada\n|Renewed\n|\n|-\n|''[[Emmerdale]]''\n|Soap opera\n|ITV\n|U.S, Canada\n|Renewed\n|\n|-\n|''[[Holby City]]''\n|Medical drama\n|BBC\n|U.S, Canada\n|Renewed\n|\n|-\n|''[[Inside No. 9]]''\n|[[Black comedy]], [[Anthology series]], [[Comedy-drama]], [[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n|BBC\n|U.S, Canada\n|Renewed\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2018/04/07/the-best-show-youre-not-watching-is-the-uk-import-inside-no-9/|title=The best show you're not watching is the UK import \"Inside No. 9\"|last=Williams|first=Mary Elizabeth|author-link=Mary Elizabeth Williams|date=7 April 2018|website=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==== Programmes for 2017 ====\nIn its debut year of 2017, the service also focused on much of the classic catalogue of British television such as:\n{{colbegin}}\n*''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]''\n*''[[Agatha Christie's Poirot]]'': The Early Cases (series 1\u20136)\n*''[[Are You Being Served?]]''\n*''[[As Time Goes By (TV series)|As Time Goes By]]''\n*''[[Blackadder]]''\n*''[[Bleak House (2005 TV serial)|Bleak House]]''\n*''[[Brideshead Revisited (TV serial)|Brideshead Revisited]]''\n*''[[Cold Feet]]''\n*''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]''\n*''[[Dalziel and Pascoe (TV series)|Dalziel and Pascoe]]''\n*''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]''\n*''[[Desperate Romantics]]''\n*''[[Doctor Who]]'' (1963\u20131989)\n*''[[Father Ted]]''\n*''[[Fawlty Towers]]''\n*''[[Gavin & Stacey]]''\n*''[[Hetty Wainthropp Investigates]]''\n*''[[Inspector Morse (TV series)|Inspector Morse]]''\n*''[[Keeping Up Appearances]]''\n*''[[Maigret (2016 TV series)|Maigret]]''\n*''[[Marley's Ghosts]]''\n*''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''\n*''[[Miss Marple (TV series)|Miss Marple]]''\n*''[[The Moonstone]]''\n*''[[New Blood (TV series)|New Blood]]''\n*''[[NW (novel)#Film|NW]]''\n*''[[The Office (UK TV series)|The Office (UK)]]*''\n*''[[Prime Suspect]]''\n*''[[Red Dwarf]]''\n*''[[Rosemary & Thyme]]''\n*''[[Scott & Bailey]]''\n*''[[Sharpe (TV series)|Sharpe]]''<ref name=engadget />\n*''[[Sherlock Holmes (1984 TV series)|Sherlock Holmes]]''\n*''[[Silent Witness]]''\n*''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs Downstairs]]''\n*''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''\n*''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]''\n{{colend}}\n\n''*Shared with [[HBO Max]] when it launches in 2020.''\n\nIn 2017, it was said there are more than 2,000 of hours of programming available on launch. A BritBox spokesperson said this number will change, as new shows are \u201cadded daily.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/british-tv-streaming-service-britbox-launches-in-u-s/|title=British TV streaming service BritBox launches in U.S.|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\nMore than 3,600 hours of programmes are currently{{when|date=February 2019}} available, with new shows  \u201cadded daily\". The programming is offered without commercial interruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/british-tv-streaming-service-britbox-launches-in-u-s/|title=British TV streaming service BritBox launches in&nbsp;U.S.|last=Perez|first=Sarah|publisher=|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nContent made by/for ITV and the BBC which is currently licensed to other streaming platforms such as Netflix, would be removed once their licences expire.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 1 August 2019, upcoming [[HBO Max]] announced its acquisition of library rights to several [[BBC Studios]] series, including the first 11 seasons of the 2005 [[Doctor Who]] revival, as well as future seasons 12\u201314. [[The Honourable Woman]], [[Luther (TV series)|Luther]], [[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]], and the British version of [[The Office (British TV series)|The Office]] are also some other shows in the acquisition. HBO Max will also stream future seasons of Doctor Who after their initial run on [[BBC America]]. Newer Doctor Who would be exclusive to HBO Max, with the other shows in the deal sold on a non-exclusive basis.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Britbox logo stacked canada flavour.png|thumb|BritBox Canada-inspired Stacked Logo]]\n\n=== Canada ===\nBritBox launched in Canada on 14 February 2018,<ref name=\":3\" /> on launch the service included a free 7-day trial and in which content can be streamed on the web, on an [[App Store (iOS)|iOS app]], [[Apple TV (software)|Apple TV]], [[Google Play|Android]], [[Samsung TVs]], [[Chromecast]] and [[Roku]]. It comes with a free 7-day introductory trial, and priced at $8.99 CAD per month on launch.<ref name=\"iphoneincanada.ca\"/> Users who signed up for the service in the U.S. will be able to access their subscription in Canada.\n\nThe catalogue of content on the Canadian platform is similar to the American platform, but minor differences do exist, for example Coronation Street isn't on Canadian BritBox, due to CBC Television holding the Canadian broadcasting rights.\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:Britbox UK Logo.png|thumb|BritBox UK Logo]]\n\nBritBox launched in the UK on 7 November 2019 with a 30-day free trial and a subscription price of \u00a35.99 per month with no minimum term contract for HD viewing and multi-screen viewing.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/nov/07/britbox-uk-networks-plan-to-tackle-netflix-amazon-and-apple-tv|title=BritBox: UK networks' plan to tackle Netflix, Amazon and Apple TV+|date=7 November 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Unlike other platforms, the UK platform would include content from BBC, ITV, Channel 4, Film 4, Channel 5 and Comedy Central UK.\n\n=== Other markets ===\nBritBox currently only has platforms in Canada, the United Kingdom and the United States, however on 15 October 2019, BBC Studios global distribution president Paul Dempsey admitted there were more markets where the UK-skewing service could work.<!-- +features -->\n\n== Information ==\n\n=== Requirements ===\nBritBox is only available to residents of Canada, the United Kingdom and the United States. UK residents can watch BritBox when temporarily outside the UK but within the [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britbox.co.uk/help|title=BritBox \u2013 Help & Support|website=www.britbox.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> Canadian and US residents can use BritBox in both Canada and the US (with differences in show availability due to rights restrictions) but it cannot be used outside of North America (including the UK version of BritBox while in the UK).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britbox.com/us/help|title=BritBox \u2013 Help & Support|website=www.britbox.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Minimal technical requirements ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Operating system\n!Version\n!Developer\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n|[[Windows 7|7]] or later\n|[[Microsoft]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n|[[Android 4.4|4.4]] (Kitkat) or later\n|[[Google]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[MacOS|Mac OS]]\n|[[OS X Mavericks|OS X 10.9 Mavericks]] or later\n|[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[iOS]]\n|[[IOS 9|9.3]] or later\n|[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n=== Supported web browsers ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Supported browsers\n!Version\n!Developer\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Google Chrome|Chrome]]\n| \u2013\n|[[Google]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Firefox]]\n| \u2013\n|[[Mozilla Foundation|Mozilla]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Opera (web browser)|Opera]]\n| \u2013\n|[[Opera Software]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Microsoft Edge|Edge]]\n|Stable\n|[[Microsoft]]\n|Under 2 years old\n|-\n|[[Safari (web browser)|Safari]]\n|Latest and previous stable major version\n|[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Android web browser|Android]]\n|Native\n|[[Google]]\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n=== Compatible devices ===\n''When accessing BritBox not via a web browser''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Products\n!Developer\n!Device type(s)\n!Notes\n!Platform\n!Software\n!Date added\n|-\n|[[iPhone]]\n|[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n|[[Smartphone]], [[Mobile device]]s\n|Labelled as '[[List of iOS devices|iOS device]]' in Help & Support, unsure if this includes the [[iPod Touch]]\n|All\n|Dedicated app\n|March 2017 (US)\nNovember 2019 (UK)\n|-\n|[[iPad]]\n|[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n|[[Tablet computer]]\n|Labelled as '[[List of iOS devices|iOS device]]' in Help & Support and 'iOS tablet'  in an ITV press release,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/britbox/press-releases/britbox-confirms-first-wave-distribution-partners|title=BritBox confirms first wave of distribution partners|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> likely includes [[iPad]], which now uses [[iPadOS]]\n|All\n|Dedicated app\n|March 2017 (US)\nNovember 2019 (UK)\n|-\n|[[Android (operating system)|Android Devices]]\n|([[Google]])\n'''Android phone manufacturers'''\n\nincluding:\n\n[[Samsung Galaxy|Samsung]]\n\n[[Huawei]]\n\n[[LG Corporation|LG]]\n\n[[Google Pixel|Google]]\n\n[[Sony Mobile|Sony]]\n\n''among others''\n|[[Touchscreen]] mobile devices ([[Smartphone]]s and [[Tablet computer|Tablets]])\n| \u2013\n|All\n|Dedicated app\n|March 2017 (US)\nNovember 2019 (UK)\n<br />\n|-\n|[[Apple TV]]\n|[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n|[[Set-top box]] [[microconsole]]\n| (TVOS) 4th Generation or later\n|All\n|Dedicated TV app\n|March 2017 (US)\nNovember 2019 (UK)\n<br />\n|-\n|[[Samsung Electronics|Samsung Tizen TV]]\n|[[Samsung]]\n|[[Smart TV]] (2016 onwards)\n|A partnership has been confirmed with Samsung, which will see the BritBox app hosted on Samsung Tizen TVs* from launch onwards (UK).\n\n\"Samsung will be the first TV to launch the BritBox app and together, Samsung and BritBox have agreed to a co-marketing partnership that will see BritBox featured as a \"Recommended App\" on Samsung Smart 